I began having hives on my legs on August 17th, but I would only have one or two at  a time and I am allergic to tons of grasses and trees so I thought my dogs had probably rolled in something and then touched me. The hives continued through August on and off and then as we moved into September,  I was getting them more frequently. I would wake up with them in the morning put hydrocortisone cream on them and take my Claritin. Within an hour they would go away. Sometimes they would come back in the afternoon and evening, but mostly in the morning. I was trying to figure out if it was environment, but I was getting them in different locations (my house, my mom's house, my brother's house) so I started to think it might be something internal. Late September is when I started getting them on my trunk (mostly my ribcage and pelvic regions) and they were big welt like hives. This started happening every morning and it was a deep hard welt that was warm to the touch . Then in mid October, I started get them every day with more than just one or two and by the beginning of November I would wake up with them all over my trunk, back and legs. I received a shot of steriods to my butt and that helped to reduce them for about a week and then I had a repeat of hives all over at which point I took oral steroids and that seems to be working right now.
LAB_DATA: I took an allergy test in early November and my IGe levels came back at close to 600.

I thought this booster would be a breeze, as the only reaction to my second Moderna vaccine was, besides a sore arm for a few days, a slight headache and tiredness, that was alleviated with Tylenol and only lasted about 24 hrs. I was fine with the Moderna booster until approximately 6 hrs later, I felt ill, had extreme chills, muscle and joint aches. The spasms from chills tightened my back and chest muscles for minutes at a time. The spasms, joint and muscle aches were intermittent and lasted for more than 24 hrs.  I felt ill all the next day but didn't vomit and took Tylenol, drank lots of liquids and rested. That night I awoke and was drenched in sweat, to the point of getting up, changing my nightgown, putting a towel down on the wet sheets and sleeping again. I was still felt tired on waking, but felt a little better. Drank fluids, took Tylenol at intervals,some soups, and rested. I just felt tired with a headache the next day and today I feel well this morning. I had a similar reaction to the second shingles shot I received, with spasms, dizziness, and chills, but it only lasted about 6hrs and was fine after that. Hope this report helps others.
PRIOR_VAX: second Shingles shot. only lasted approx 6hrs

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient's mother brought patient in to receive a COVID-19 Pfizer vaccine on 08/31/2021.  The patient?s mother filled out a consent form on behalf of the patient and listed the date of birth and signed and consented on the official Health Department Pfizer-BioNTech consent form.  The nurse verified the name and date of birth with the patient and the patient?s mother.  Public Health guidelines were followed, and the parent received the up-to-date Pfizer-BioNTech EUA and the vaccine was administered.  In the patient?s 15-minute wait there were no adverse reactions. Three weeks later, on 09/21/2021 the mother once again filled out a consent form and stated her child's birthday. Upon entering the vaccine into the Immunization Information System it was discovered that the patient's true DOB was different and therefore this was an unauthorized vaccination.  The date of birth was then confirmed and verified in the System.  The Public Health Department Medical Director was notified.  In addition, the patient's parent/guardian was informed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Symptoms started on July 14th. What started as a pain in my left upper back, and felt like a pinched nerve, developed over the next 3 days into an excruciating pain that made it difficult to stand up. The pain was centered in my left scapular muscles and caused tingling, numbness, weakness and muscle spasms in my left tricep, back and pec. After about a week the pain started to subside but the weakness persisted. After a month of weakness and pain I noticed muscular atrophy in my left tricep, pec and scapular muscles. This is around the time I had my first visit with my orthopedic doctor.  XRays came back clear with no injuries, as did MRIs but EMG showed that there was nerve damage in my left tricep and pec. It wasn't until I saw a Dr. in early November of 2021 that she suggested that I had experienced Parsonage Turners Syndrome. Since then we have started physical therapy as treatment.
LAB_DATA: EMG - Evidence for left C6 radiculopathy with ongoing denervation - 10/07/2021 MRI - Normal - 10/29/2021

On April 20, 2021, in the late afternoon I was talking on the phone while doing a presentation for work like I normally do every day. As I was talking, I noticed I couldn't catch my breath, so I ended the call. I was sitting and just talking. I looked at my smart watch and it said my heart rate was 150 bpm at rest. I called an ambulance and when they arrived my blood pressure was 170 over something and it was high. I usually don't have high blood pressure. They took me to ER. The doctors ran test but couldn't find anything, so I was discharged. It kept happening at night where I would be short of breath, have chest pains, and a racing heart rate. I didn't have anxiety or anything like that before. I went to my family Doctor, and he prescribed metoprolol 25mg 1xday to try to calm my heart rate down. I got my second dose on April 24th, 2021. I had a Holter monitor that came back fairly normal. In May my heart rate flew up to 150 again. I went to the doctor again. They did some more test, and everything was normal. I've seen a cardiologist on June 3, 2021. I have been on metoprolol ever since my doctor has prescribed it. I haven't been to the ICU anymore because my doctor said I can just take the metoprolol to keep my heart from racing. Every couple of months I have a flare up, and I have never had this before getting the vaccine. About every 2 months I have been having the flare ups with my heart. I am starting to feel better overtime.
LAB_DATA: Bloodwork- slightly low magnesium (April 20, 2021)  Echocardiogram- normal (June 23, 2021)  Lab Panel- magnesium was normal (September 3, 2021)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: It happened on Saturday 10/9. I had just eaten lunch and I have a sensor for my blood sugar in my arm. I was looking at the TV and my vision turned into kaleidoscope vision for 2 minutes. I tested my blood sugar, and it was 140 which is normal for me. I called my PCP, and we went to the hospital - Hospital. Evaluated for detached retina. They did a verbal stroke test and checked to see if it was going to be a stroke. They put dye in my eye, but they didn't have the equipment to check my eye but checked for scratches. Nothing was found and we went home after. 10/12 went to the ophthalmologist and did a bunch of tests and determined that my eyes were fine. PCP said that if it happened again to go to the hospital. I went home, and the next time I had it, it was just one eye. It seemed like a lightning bolt in one eye. We went to Hospital 10/23, and they gave me a CAT scan and MRI. They couldn't find anything in my brain that would be causing it. The doctor there thought that it could have been an ocular migraine. We went to Dr. 10/22021 where he said it was confirmed an ocular migraine. It happened about 2 to 3 more times. It switches back and forth between eyes. I've never gotten headaches with it. The time I went to the doctor, I was nauseous, but that could have been due to other factors.
LAB_DATA: Verbal stroke test  normal Eye exam with contrast dye  normal Extensive eye examination at ophthalmologist - nothing was wrong with eyes CAT Scan - nothing found MRI - nothing found Chest X-ray  normal Blood work  normal Ultrasound for corrode artery - normal Chest xray - normal Blood work - normal  Ultrasound for corrode artery - normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The morning of 11/17/2021, the day after vaccine, I had a light headache and abdominal cramping. The cramping kind of progressed. The period started abnormal and throughout the day it became excessively heavy. I had to use multiple sanitary pads throughout the day. I do have fibroids, and I read, if you have fibroids the vaccine can make your menstrual heavy. I bled all over my brand-new car seats and I had excessive bleeding all over my bed sheet. The puddle was like a 1-foot puddle on my side the following morning. I did not go to work the next day because I was constantly changing. I had a headache for a total of 4 days, and I tried to take everything I can before I take Imitrex. I finally had to take Imitrex and slept the following day and my headache was finally gone. Today, 11/22/2021 I finally woke up with no headache. I contacted my clinic and had a telephone conference regarding my symptoms. They told me to stay home because it was a side effect of the vaccine.

Hospitalized (11.16.21 -discharged 11/20/21; COVID-19 positive (11.16.21); Fully vaccinated   HOSPITAL COURSE: Patient is a 69M  with a history of pulmonary fibrosis and right prosthetic knee infection with MSSA status post right total knee replacement in July.  He completed 6 weeks IV cefazolin then transition to cephalexin.  He had relapse infection with additional OR on October 20th.  Intraoperative cultures grew Serratia and patient currently is on cefepime through December 7th.  He follows with Dr. from pulmonary and currently is not on home oxygen or steroids due to underlying knee infection.     He presented to Emergency Department with 2 days of acute worsening in his shortness of breath.  Minimal exertion makes the symptoms worse.  He has productive cough with chills but no fever.  Patient has received full vaccinations for COVID-19 (J and J).  On arrival to emergency department he was found to be hypoxic with oxygen saturation 70% room air.  Supplemental oxygen was placed with improvement to mid 90s.  He did undergo CT angiogram thorax which was negative for pulmonary embolism but had new superimposed mosaic attenuation throughout both lung fields question developing pulmonary edema or infectious etiology.  His BNP was normal, COVID-19 was not detected, procalcitonin was normal.   He was given 20 mg IV Lasix and transferred to another facility for ongoing care.   Film array was ordered which eventually showed positive for COVID-19.  He was started on Decadron 6 mg daily with plan to complete a 10 day treatment course.  He also received Remdesivir for 5 days.  He was seen by infectious disease who recommended continuing cefepime through 12/07/2021.   Pulmonary medicine recommended to continue Symbicort inpatient and albuterol p.r.n..  He is scheduled for outpatient follow-up with the Pulmonary office on 12/28   He continues to remain stable and required 3 L of oxygen with rest and 4 L of O2 with ambulation.  He will be out of COVID isolation on 11/24/2021   He was discharged home in stable condition on 11/20/2020 CONSULTS / RECOMMENDATION:   Consult Orders (From admission, onward)    IP CONSULT TO INFECTIOUS DISEASES      Provider:  MD   IP CONSULT TO PULMONOLOGY      Provider:  MD

Pt appeared to have slight cough when presenting for vaccination. Patient was asked a series of questions before receiving Vaccine including the patient's current status and whether they are currently having any symptoms of Covid, Illness, or Infection. Patient denied any symptoms. Patient continued to have a slight but constant cough. Patient was given Pfizer Covid Vaccine First Dose 0.3mg. Within two minutes the patient began to show signs of anxious behavior. Patient suddenly said he "needs to walk" and got up from his chair. He walked down a small hallway with the LPN who administered the Vaccine following close behind. Patient was asked if he was SOB and he stated he was. Patient sat down in waiting room. Patient was asked to return to the Covid Vaccine Clinic for assessment. On his way back to the Clinic, the patient had to take many pauses to breath. Patient was asked if the SOB was sudden after receiving Vaccine and patient denied this and stated that he was feeling SOB prior to arriving. Upon return to the Covid Vaccine Clinic the patient had an SpO2 attached and patient's O2 was at 81% on room air.  Emergency Response Team was notified of situation. O2 was provided at 2L via cannula and patient SpO2 raised to 85%. Patient's PCP was notified and responded to the Covid Vaccine Clinic. Physician was informed of vitals and immediately had EMS called. 02 was increased to 4L and patient's levels raised to 89% but began to decline to 86%. Patient exhibited tachycardia and was diaphoretic. 02 was increased to 6L with patient declining to 84%. EMS arrived and took over control of care.   Upon arrival, he had complaints of nausea and vomited multiple times. He was placed on monitor and oxygen saturations were reading 53% and HR 120's with rhythm concerning for atrial fibiralltion. He became minimally responsive requiring BVM and was then emergently intubated for airway protection with etomidate, succinylcholine, 150 mcg of fentanyl and 3 mg of IV ativan. After intubation, he became profoundly hypotensive with SBP 50s and MAPs in the 30s. He was given 100 mcg of IVP phenylephrine and was initiated on Norepinephrine infusion to maintain MAPs > 65. His initial troponin-1 was 196 . He was started on a Heparin infusion and bedside ECHO with EF 35%.  Diagnosed with Stress-induced cardiomyopathy with  Takotsubo presentation.  Of note, since being diagnosed with COVID 19 in October 2020 he had worsening dyspnea with intermittent chest pain., but had not yet followed up with pulmonary and cardiology docs.

Patient was on 2 L of nasal cannula at the outside facility and saturating in the mid 90s.  Patient's blood pressure initially was in the 140 systolic however dropped to 80s though asymptomatic.  The patient was given normal saline boluses which her blood pressure was responsive.  Due to elevated procalcitonin was started on 1 g of ceftriaxone and 500 mg of azithromycin.  Was briefly on norepinephrine however this was weaned off without difficulty.  Patient was initially to be transferred to the ICU however with improvement was transferred to General Medicine. Denies chest pain, shortness of breath, dyspnea on exertion, pleuritic pain, abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea.  States she has had some fevers at her facility.  Tells me that she typically has low blood pressures.  Her biggest complaint is the neuropathy in her feet.

24 hours after, began to notice a mild tightness in my chest ? on the left side.  Sensation came and went. Brief periods of being aware of the tightness followed by long intervals without sensation. Never painful, never distressing, just mildly there on and off.  After 24 hours sensation had not gone away. Decided to go to ER (~48 hours after the shot)  out of concern for heart. At the ER, EKG was normal, traponin levels were normal (tested it twice), chest x-ray was normal, CT with contrast showed no sign of a clot.  I did not have swelling in my legs, nor any difficulty breathing, so the doctor ruled out myocarditis.  I left ER without an explanation and with instructions to follow-up with a cardiologist.  I waited a few more days to see if the sensation would go away. It didn?t. During this time, the pattern was pretty much the same as before, but some new sensations  emerged.  A few times, I had a sharp ?lightning bolt? that lasted only a second but was like a zap.    Once it became clear that the problem was ongoing, I made an appointment with a cardiologist.  I had a tele-health appointment with her on Friday, 11/19. She believes that the shot induced mild inflammation.  She told me to take ibuprofen and within a day or so the symptoms (mostly) subsided.  I am continuing to take the ibuprofen and will stop after a full week.  The doctor ordered an echocardiogram and EKG, which I will have after the holiday.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hospitalized (11.5.21 -discharged 11/14/21; COVID-19 positive (11.4.21); Fully vaccinated  HOSPITAL COURSE: Patient is a 36 y.o. female with a known history of COPD, asthma, recurrent pancreatitis related to hypertriglyceridemia, type 2 diabetes uncontrolled, anxiety, depression, PTSD and morbid obesity who presented to the ED with three days of epigastric pain on 11/4/21. In the ED, she was tachycardic with VS otherwise stable. Labs notable for Na 127, glucose 318, TG 2540. COVID PCR was positive. CXR showed no acute pathology. CT abd/pelvis showed inflammatory process in the distal duodenum, pancreas head and uncinate process with a fluid collection. Patient was given 1L IVF and admitted for abdominal pain 2/2 possible pancreatitis.   Upon admission, she was evaluated by the GI team who recommended treatment of hypertriglyceridemia with insulin gtt as well as ongoing IV hydration.  She remained on insulin drip for several days with improvement triglycerides. She was converted to BBI per DGMS recs and blood glucose remained stable. At discharge DGMS recommending resuming home insulin and oral antihyperglycemic regimen.   Regarding COVID, patient received monoclonal antibodies while on room air.  She was thought to be nearing discharge when she began to require supplemental oxygen up to max of 6L.  There was concern for hypervolemia due to the amount of IV fluids she had received, but BNP was normal and CXR without evidence of pulmonary vascular congestion.  Patient was started on remdesivir and Decadron. Completed 4 days of therapy. Oxygen was able to be weaned off completely during the day but she continued having mild desats at night on overnight oximetry study. She is in process of being diagnosed w/ OSA and has follow up sleep study scheduled. Home Oxygen was prescribed for NC 2L at night. Patient discharged with instructions to follow up with DGMS and PCP outpatient. Patient in agreement with discharge plan and discharged in stable condition. SYMPTOM_TEXT: First dose after a couple of days, I started feeling the shortness of breath and it started getting worse especially in the evening. I would be gasping for air sometimes and would occur every few minutes throughout the day and eventually tapered off after a couple weeks with it occasionally happening again. As per treatment, I had a visit phone visit 4/29/2021 about shortness of breath and chest tightness. The day after or the day after that, I went to the urgent care, and they did an echocardiogram of my heart. They said everything was fine. I asked if I should see a pulmonologist and the urgent care doctor said sure. 5/5 I went to the pulmonologist, he chatted with me about the symptoms and ran some tests. He prescribed me an inhaler, but I was scared to use it because I was breast feeding. I also did a blood test, and everything was normal with that as well. Complete blood test, D-dimer, and a little anemic I have been for a while. June 23, pulmonary function test normal. I did do a COVID-19 test on 5/7 and it was negative as well. 6 days after the dose, it looked like I had a bite on my arm and spread over the night that turned into a large pink rash. I messaged my dermatologist about it, and they said that it was a normal reaction for the Moderna shot. Went away after a few days.
LAB_DATA: Echocardiogram normal Blood test a little anemic normal D-dimer normal Pulmonary function test normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client stated, "I was sitting in my chair for 2 minutes and then I began to feel a rush to my head. It felt like a wave of tingling all over my body and I started to feel disoriented for like 10 seconds. I then felt fine but I said to myself I need to get up and let the nurse know." Secondary RN helped transfer client into anti-gravity chair at 12:05 PM. First set of vitals were then taken at that time by Observation RN prior to Co Lead PHN responding to observation room: BP 115/75, pulse 60, O2 SAT 100%, 16 respirations per minute. At 12:08 PM Co Lead PHN advised client to take face mask off and for client to take deep breaths. Client was offered water and snacks but client declined snacks and already had a water bottle. Client stated, "I am not surprised I felt like this after the shot because back when I received my first Janssen shot the next day I felt slight chest tightness while driving. It only lasted for 15 seconds then I felt fine. I am not sure if it was due to the covid-19 vaccine so I didn't feel the need to let my doctor know." Co Lead PHN clarified whether she was short of breath during that experience while driving to which client said "no." Client stated, "I felt like I was gasping for air and not so much choking. It only lasted for 15 seconds while I was driving and I then felt fine." Client then disclosed to Co Lead PHN, "I've had similar experiences with blood draws where I feel like I'm going to faint." Client does not have any medical conditions nor is taking any medications. Client has no history of allergies. Client did state, "I am sensitive to soaps, lotions, and I always take half the dose of any medication." Co Lead PHN observed client to be A&Ox4 throughout entire conversation. Co lead PHN recommended for client to follow up with PCP regarding post vaccination symptoms and to enroll in V-SAFE. Client stated, "I have an appointment with my PCP on Tuesday, I will let them know." At 12:16 PM secondary RN educated the client on when to call 911 or go to urgent care for adverse symptoms of covid-19 vaccination. Client verbalized understanding. Co Lead PHN recommended for client to call a family member to assist the client in driving home to which client declined because she only lives 1 mile away from vaccination site. Co Lead PHN recommended for one last set of vitals after another 10 minutes of monitoring. at 12:27 PM Secondary RN took last set of vitals: BP LA 115/70, pulse 64, O2 SAT 100%. Client expressed she was ready to go home. At 12:31 PM Co Lead PHN walked with client as standby assist towards the exit of vaccination site. Client walked with steady gait and thanked us for assisting her.

The day I got the vaccine I was fine. As the month progressed, I started felling uncoordinated. I started getting more cluster migraines up to the day I had my stroke on April 12, 2021. I was taken by ambulance on April 12,2021 because my right side had gone numb. When I arrived they gave me blood clotting medicine. The RN stated that the client was not upset and agreed to allow the RN to repeat the process of re-administering the COVID19 Moderna booster shot. The RN educated the client on both the potential side effects and adverse effects of the vaccine, when to seek medical attention, and ER precautions.  Afterward, the client was escorted to the observation area for a 15-minute observation and no issues were noted.  At approximately 12:30, the RN notified the Lead RN of the administration error. The Lead RN explained to the RN that a Lead Nurse should be notified immediately of any vaccine administration errors before proceeding with re-vaccination. Within 1 to 2 minutes of administering the Janssen Covid Vaccine to the patient, the patient fainted while waiting in the observation area at the front of the pharmacy. His wife yelled to staff that he had fainted and wasn't sure if he may be having a seizure. The pharmacist immediately approached the patient, who did not appear to be having a seizure, although she did observe that his face was drained of color (white/gray), and the patient was unresponsive, his eyes were shut. The patient did have a pulse and was breathing normally. At this time, a pharmacy technician was contacting 911 emergency medical services, who were on their way to the pharmacy. A second pharmacist approached to help the patient immediately, and the patient started to wake, and become responsive to verbal cues from his spouse and pharmacy staff. The second pharmacist conducted neurological tests (checked patient's eyes, ability to speak, maneuver arms), and the patient was given orange juice to drink. The patient blood pressure and heart rate were checked (119/95, 41 bpm). The patient became very apologetic and embarrassed (he stated this), and it was explained that he had a history of fainting in response to seeing needles previously (i.e., during blood draw). The patient was able to drink a few gulps of orange juice. Within the first few minutes of waking, the patient then fainted again. He was not responsive for about a minute, and then became responsive again, as EMS arrived. EMS than evaluated the patient, and offered to take him to the ER, which the patient declined. The patient signed a release to not go to the ER, and returned home for the evening, but was instructed to seek medical attention if further warranted at any time.
LAB_DATA: The patients blood pressure and heart rate was checked (119/95, 41 bpm).

Client came to our facility requesting a Modern booster shot.  She explained to the RN that she received her 1st dose of the COVID19 Pfizer vaccine on 12/21/2020, and approximately 5 minutes later, the client experienced a rapid heartbeat for approximately 30 seconds.  She experienced no other side effects from the 1st shot of the vaccine.  The client received her 2nd shot of the COVID19 Pfizer vaccine on 1/11/21 and 5 minutes later experienced numbness in her cheeks, which lasted for approximately 2 minutes.  The client did not experience a rapid heart rate with her 2nd dose or any other side effects.  The RN communicated this information to the Lead RN who conducted a medical consult with Clinical Lead.  Due to the client experiencing reactions to her 1st & 2nd dose of the Pfizer vaccine within the first 4 hours of receiving the vaccine, the Clinical Lead escalated the issue to the County doctor for approval.  The doctor gave approval for the client to receive the COVID19 Moderna booster shot (Lot#FF8841) with a 30-minute observation period.  The RN administered the shot at approximately 13:30 and educated the client on both the potential side effects and adverse effects of the vaccine, when to seek medical attention, and ER precautions.   The client was escorted to the observation area where she observed for 30 minutes, and no issues were noted.

Patient came in 9:40 AM to get his booster 0.25 mL Moderna vaccine. At 9:54 AM, patient came back describing feeling of throat swelling, restrictive, and back of throat feeling scratchy. Pharmacist checked on his pulse (120 HR) and O2 sensor (98%). Patient was able to talk freely and swallow water and feeling "freaked out", which explains his high HR. At 10:00, when arrived, I looked at his throat, tongue, pharynx, uvula, and mouth. No swelling was seen. No tenderness of throat. Patient mentioned it is still scratchy but does not feel restrictive anymore. At 10:05 AM, O2 sensor (99%) and HR (80%) were consistent with not having an anaphylactic shock, however due to throat scratchiness. Recommended to give 50 mg diphenhydramine and 20 mg famotidine (verbal order from ED doctor in  Regional hospital). Patient was able to swallow pills without issues. Recommended to monitor for 30 minutes. At 10:40 AM, Patient was doing well. Throat scratch was a little better. HR and O2 sensor were 80 and 99%, respectively. Advised the patient to go home and monitor himself. Give us a call if condition gets worse. Counseled that he could be drowsy and someone should take him home.   Called patient at home at 11:50 Am and he was doing really well breathing fine. Will call again before evening shift. Recommended to go to emergency department if condition gets worse.  Called patient at home 3:39 PM and he states full recovery.

Pt is a 46 y/o male with a chief complaint of vasovagal reaction after receiving his 2nd CoV2-Moderna .5ml vaccine via IM route.   At/around 1712 the pt was received a second Moderna vaccine via IM while in seated in the driver?s location of his vehicle. The pt then drove from the vaccine administration area to the observation area, approximately 100ft away. The pt had informed the administration nurse that he had "passed out" after receiving his first Cov2 Moderna vaccination. The nurse informed me and the other paramedic on site. Continued contact was maintained with the pt during his observation period, at/around 1720 the pt stated he was not feeling well. When asked how he felt, he stated "I feel like I'm going to pass out." His skin was becoming very flush. I was laying his seat back when the pt lost consciousness, I made sure to stabilize the pts head and neck. I then laid the pt back in his seat placing him in a modified supine position. Pts vitals were assessed with a radial pule rate of 90bpm strong and regular, RR of 20 witgh adequate chest rise and fall, SV pall cool and clammy, pupils equal and reactive to light.  My partner had retrieved the medic kit and placed ice packs in the pts armpits and behind his neck. within 45-50 seconds the pt regained consciousness. The pt was startled and confused. We reassured the pt we were just here to help and explained what had happened. The pt remained calm and was instructed to continue to lay back. Vitals were reassessed with the following SV slightly pale, warm, and dry, pupils pearl, radial pulse rate 68bpm with no abnormalities, BP 125/80. Pt stated ?I?m beginning to feel much better.? Five minutes later the pt was aaox4, SV: pink warm and dry, pupils: pearl, BP and pulse rate remained the same. Pt was then asked to exit his vehicle and stand with our assistance. Pts pulse remained 67-69bpm strong and regular. Pt the stood without assistance and stated, ?I feel much better and do not feel lightheaded or dizzy at all.? Pt demographics were obtained and pt was released.
LAB_DATA: supportive care, continued vitals, ice packs.

Lumbar/sacrum pain and testicular pain reduced to a level 4-5 using a combination of meloxicam, tramadol 50mg 4x/day and pregabalin 25mg 3X/day for 5 days following vaccine administration. I was able to stop using tramadol after 5 days and continued to use pregabalin, which keeps the chronic pain to a level 4. Urinary hesitancy increased following the 2nd dose of the vaccine and hasn't returned to levels experienced before the 2nd dose of Moderna vaccine. Pain levels and urinary hesitancy increased significantly following the administration of the 2nd dose of the Moderna vaccine requiring additional daily medications for pain management. The benefits of the vaccine don't outweigh the increased chronic pain levels. Chronic pelvic pain syndrome must be listed as a adverse reaction to the Moderna vaccine so that patients can have a conversation with the physician about the benefits verses the risk prior to receiving the 2nd does of the Moderna vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: mild fatigue; brief unusual nerve pain; burning pain in my knee area; pain is happening beneath the skin of the knees / related to the skin above the knee; feel inflamed; they burn / burning joint pain/burning sensation in joints/burning knee pain, he cannot kneel; his elbows and both knees are sensitive; tingling sensation going down left; sore arm at the injection site; This case was reported by a other health professional and described the occurrence of injection site pain in a 60-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. In October 2021, less than a week after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced tingling sensation. On 29th October 2021, the patient experienced injection site pain. On 10th November 2021, the patient experienced sensitive skin. On 11th November 2021, the patient experienced burning sensation in joints. On an unknown date, the patient experienced fatigue, nerve pain, pain burning, skin pain and knee arthritis. The patient was treated with naproxen (Naprosyn). On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site pain, nerve pain and tingling sensation were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the fatigue, knee arthritis and sensitive skin were unknown and the outcome of the pain burning, skin pain and burning sensation in joints were not recovered/not resolved.   The reporter considered the injection site pain to be related to Shingrix. It was unknown if the reporter considered the fatigue, nerve pain, pain burning, skin pain, burning sensation in joints, knee arthritis, sensitive skin and tingling sensation to be related to Shingrix.  Additional case details were provided as follows: The case was reported by the patient. The patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix in left arm, initial side effects were mild and unexpected, about 8 hours after the Shingrix injection patient's arm was sore at the injection site but resolved in a few days. Also had mild fatigue and a brief, unusual nerve pain that went down left leg to foot (which went away completely after it occurred). However, after 10-12 days of receiving the 1st dose of Shingrix, the patient started to develop a burning pain in right knee area.  This burning pain occurred when the patient bent knee and touched the floor, leaning on knee. This pain had continued, remains pronounced, and did not go away.  It feels like the pain was happening just beneath the skin of the knees.  Both knees appear to be affected, but it was worse on his right knee.  It feels like it was related to the skin above the knee, as the knee joint itself does not hurt.  About 24 to 36 hours after the Shingrix injection he noticed a tingling sensation that went all the way down his left leg to his foot and then went away in a few minutes.  About 5 days ago from the date of reporting on 10th November 2021 both his elbows and both knees were sensitive. The patient had a burning sensation in his right knee if he rubs the right knee it was fine, but if he touches it with a piece of fabric it burns and feel inflamed, could not kneel his right knee on the ground because of the painful burning sensation. It was much more pronounced on the right knee. The reporter asked was this burning knee pain related to the Shingrix vaccine and if so, when should he expect it to go away.  The patient had taken Motrin and Naprosyn to take the edge off his right knee.  Also asked did this burning joint pain have nothing to do with Shingrix, the patient never experienced this before taking Shingrix. The patient would appreciate receiving any documentation, research or information if GlaxoSmithKline have on this possible side effect. The reporter was waiting to hear from his HCP to see if this might be related to shingles. The reporter did not consent to follow-up.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2021235330:Same reporter, FU1 - Deleted

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Chills; Body aches/ Pain; Vomiting; Diarrhea; cramping; arm pain/ leg pain; leg pain, could not walk; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of chills in a female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) (batch number 4c493, expiry date 20th March 2023) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included Flu vaccine (received dose on an unknown date), Moderna (received 3 doses on unknown dates) and Zostavax (received dose on an unknown date).   On 6th November 2021, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular) 50 g. In November 2021, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced chills, general body pain, vomiting, diarrhea, cramp, pain in arm and unable to walk. On 7th November 2021 16:00, the outcome of the chills, general body pain, vomiting, diarrhea, cramp, pain in arm and unable to walk were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the chills, general body pain, vomiting, diarrhea, cramp, pain in arm and unable to walk to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported by the patient herself. The patient had received her 1st dose of Shingrix intramuscularly into her left deltoid at her pharmacy at around 12-1pm in the afternoon.  At 2am the next morning, she woke up with chills, body aches, vomiting, diarrhea, and cramping.  She also reported she experienced arm pain and leg pain that was so bad she could not walk.  By 4pm on 7th November 2021, she reported that all of these symptoms had resolved. The caller reported her reactions to her PCP and her doctor told her she should not get the 2nd dose of the Shingrix. The caller reported that her past vaccination history (dates unknown) included Zostavax, 3 doses of Moderna, and the flu vaccine and she has never had any reactions like she experienced after taking the initial Shingrix vaccine. The reporter consented to follow up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: ELEVATED TROPONIN; DIZZINESS; This 70-year-old, White, female subject (US0070109) was participating in "A Phase 2/3 Study to Evaluate the Immunogenicity and Safety of mRNA Vaccine Boosters for SARS-CoV-2 Variants (mRNA-1273-P205)" and experienced dizziness and elevated troponin.   The subject's medical history, as provided by the investigator, included complete hysterectomy, bilateral oophorectomy, suspected ovarian cancer, benign abdominal mass, excision benign abdominal mass, sinus bradycardia, chronic diarrhea, dyslipidemia, hypertension, type II diabetes, sensory diabetic neuropathy of bilateral feet, sulfa drugs allergy, erythromycin allergy, mild venous insufficiency, postmenopausal, smoker, minocycline allergy, and tetracycline allergy. Concomitant medications reported included potassium chloride, hydralazine, rosuvastatin, lisinopril, pregabalin, tramadol, metformin hydrochloride/sitagliptin phosphate monohydrate, acetylsalicylic acid/caffeine/paracetamol, calcium chloride/potassium chloride/sodium lactate, and magnesium.  The subject previously experienced the serious adverse event of symptomatic bradycardia (MOD-2021-258186) while participating in this study.   On 02 Jul 2021, approximately 29 days prior to the onset of the events, the subject received the single booster shot dose of mRNA-1273.211 intramuscularly, 100 micrograms (one-time dose) in the left arm in Part A of the study for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  On 30 Jul 2021, the subject experienced dizziness and elevated troponin. Subject presented to the emergency department with dizziness, diaphoresis, and nausea that morning. She denied chest pain. She reported feeling off balance. Two weeks ago, she woke up with similar symptoms but more severe. At that time, she went to the hospital and was found to be bradycardic (heart rate 32-34). She was referred to outpatient cardiology but has not followed up. The subject reported she did not drink a lot of the water the day before and that dehydration usually causes these types of symptoms. Vitals revealed pulse was 46-58 beats per minute (bpm). She was admitted because of sinus bradycardia. She was given intravenous fluids and heart rate went back to normal. Subject also endorsed a positive stress test about 20 years ago but never followed up with further evaluation. Physical exam of cardiovascular revealed regular rate. Regular rhythm. No murmurs, rubs, or gallops. Distal pulses were 2+ and symmetric. Labs revealed cardiac enzymes were elevated upon initial admission; troponin was 0.01 ng/mL (<0.01 ng/mL). The subject had a negative SARS-CoV-2 real-time reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction nasopharyngeal swab. Chest x-ray revealed normal heart size. No infiltrates were seen. Normal appearance to the pulmonary vasculature. No pleural effusion was apparent. No acute bony abnormality seen. Electrocardiogram (ECG) showed sinus bradycardia and low voltage QRS. No significant change when compared to ECG of 23 Jun 2006. Treatment included intravenous calcium chloride/ potassium chloride/ sodium lactate for dizziness and oral acetylsalicylic acid and subcutaneous enoxaparin for elevated cardiac enzymes.  On 31 Jul 2021, the subject's troponin was <0.01 ng/mL, and she remained hospitalized for further evaluation. Computerized tomogram of head and brain was normal. ECG showed sinus bradycardia and low voltage QRS. No significant change when compared to ECG from previous day. Transthoracic echocardiogram revealed left ventricular estimated ejection fraction 70%. Left ventricular size was normal. Borderline concentric left ventricular hypertrophy. No regional wall motion abnormalities. Hyperdynamic left ventricular systolic function. Benign diastolic inflow patter. No significant valve pathology. Doppler suggested normal pulmonary artery pressures.   On 01 Aug 2021, repeat troponin was within normal limits at <0.01 ng/mL. Vitals include heart rate of 52 bpm. Physical exam of cardiovascular revealed S1 and S2 normal, bradycardic no murmurs, rubs, or gallops. The subject was hemodynamically stable and cardiology cleared the subject. She was discharged from the hospital and advised to follow-up with cardiology soon after discharge for cardiac monitor placement.   On 02 Aug 2021, repeat troponin was within normal limits. Per the investigator, there was no underlying cause known to date. Dizziness can be in the setting of bradycardia and dehydration. Subject had risk factors, hypertension, and diabetes.   The subject received the single booster shot dose of study drug prior to the events; therefore, action taken with the drug in response to the events was not applicable.  The event, dizziness, was reported as resolved on 30 Jul 2021. The event, elevated troponin, was reported as resolved on 31 Jul 2021.   The investigator assessed the events, dizziness and elevated troponin, as not related to the study drug.  Follow-up received on 11 Aug 2021 included updated event term to dizziness (previously reported symptomatic bradycardia), medical history, treatment, concomitant medication details, additional AESI of elevated cardiac enzyme, and confirmation of discharge date.  Follow-up received on 14 Sep 2021 included updated event term (previously elevated cardiac enzyme), updated severity for event elevated troponin (previously mild), concomitant medications, COVID-19 test results, troponin results, medical history, and information that elevated troponin is not an AESI.  Follow-up received on 21 Sep 2021 and 22 Sep 2021 included updated event term to elevated cardiac enzymes (previous elevated troponin) and discharge summary with additional medical history, diagnostic tests, laboratory results, symptoms, and other clinical details of hospitalization.   Follow-up received on 04 Oct 2021 included updated event term (previously elevated cardiac enzymes) and confirmation of study drug arm.  Follow-up received on 15 Oct 2021 included no new information.  Follow-up received on 29 Oct 2021 included an update to the causality of the study drug for event of elevated troponin (previously reported as related) and downgrade to serious adverse event.  Follow-up received on 08 Nov 2021 included confirmation of study drug.  On 28 Sep 2021, the safety database was searched for events similar to Myocardial necrosis marker increased using the following search criteria: PT: Myocardial necrosis marker increased  As of 28 Sep 2021, under IND 019745 for mRNA-1273.211, two similar events were retrieved, including the current index case.  None of these cases reporting the following event were previously submitted as IND Safety Reports: Myocardial necrosis marker increased.  One case was a non-IND Safety Report (expected and related or unexpected and unrelated or expected and unrelated to the IMP) reporting the following event: Myocardial necrosis marker increased (1) MCN# MOD-2021-199200.  Case MOD-2021-199200: Unexpected events of elevated cardiac enzymes and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) exacerbation was experienced by a 68 year old male subject with medical history of diabetes mellitus type 2, supraventricular tachycardia, chronic obstruction pulmonary disease, hypertension, and hyperlipidemia. The events occurred 9 months 10 days after the first dose of mRNA-1273.211 vaccine and 8 months 13 days after the last dose. The events were considered unrelated to the study medication in agreement with the Investigator's assessment, noting the multiple comorbidities may remain as risk factors.  Based on review of available data, the Sponsor does not believe a cause and effect relationship has been established between administration of mRNA-1273 study vaccine and the occurrence of dizziness.  After review of the clinical details and investigator comments pertaining to this adverse event, and based upon experience to date, the Sponsor does not believe that changes to the conduct of this clinical trial are warranted. The Company will continue to monitor these and other serious adverse events reported in association with the IMP and will communicate any relevant changes to the protocol, Informed Consent Form, Investigator's Brochure, and/or Core Safety Information.; Reporter's Comments: This case concerns a 70-year-old, White, female subject with a medical history of dyslipidemia, hypertension, type II diabetes, sensory diabetic neuropathy, complete hysterectomy, bilateral oophorectomy, suspected ovarian cancer, benign abdominal mass, excision benign abdominal mass, sinus bradycardia and chronic diarrhea who experienced dizziness and elevated troponin. The events happened 29 days after receiving single booster shot dose of mRNA-1273.211, and both events resolved within two days. The event elevated troponin was initially assessed as related to mRNA-1273.211 by the sponsor and the investigator and finally it was reassessed as not related to IP in agreement with the Investigator. The event dizziness was assessed as unrelated to mRNA-1273.211 in agreement with the Investigator. The event dizziness might be explained by the subject's medical history of sinus bradycardia and type II diabetes.

Reportedly, the patient reported that her course of pregnancy and delivery was smooth and without complications, however, the delivery type was not specified. In addition, the patient experienced the non-serious expected event of Headache after receiving the first dose of mRNA vaccine. It was reported that on Friday 05-Nov-2021 I noticed intense itchiness on head, neck, and shoulders in the morning and it persisted on and off throughout the day. The same occurred the next morning. On Sunday 07-Nov-2021 the itch spread over the entire body along with redness and hives. Full body includes face, scalp, palms, feet, and everything else. Patient had felt no relief with Benadryl (oral and topical) nor with colloidal oatmeal treatments. Patient had went to Urgent care and was told to continue taking Benadryl. Patient was prescribed Prednisone but urged not to take it. On Monday 08-Nov-2021 the rash persisted. Patient had started taking Zyrtec in addition to Benadryl. Patient added Vitamin C and Calcium to daily medication. The rash persisted on 09-Nov-2021 again so patient returned to Urgent Care (at a different location) and was told to take Zyrtec and Pepcid in the mornings followed by Benadryl at night. Patient was also given a prescription for Methylprednisolone tapered over 6 days and instructed to take it if patient could not take the rash anymore. The doctor also recommended patient to see an allergist to get to the root of the breakout. On Wednesday 10-Nov-2021. Patient had started taking Methylprednisolone, carefully as instructed. Patient had started feeling the hives waning on Saturday 13-Nov-2021 and eventually becoming minimal on 15-Nov-2021 with a few patches on the neck in the morning.    This case was linked to MOD-2021-385740 (Patient Link). For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments.   No concomitant medications reported. Treatment included sleep, antibiotics, steroids, drinking a lot of water and physical therapy. At the end of august patient had a day where patient was out in the sun for a long time then felt like  had heat stroke. That Saturday night the throat started to hurt, patient had a head cold, felt bad, and tired. Patient took Theraflu, started sleeping more, and drinking a lot of water. Patient  did not have any fever, trouble breathing, or congestion. The symptoms lasted a week before resolving. After this all went away, the next day patient woke up with a pain behind the right ear. The day after the ear pain continued and patient woke up with the right side of the face not working. Patient went to see the HCP who gave a covid test which was negative, and prescribed antibiotics and steroids. Patient was diagnosed with bells palsy. Patient had follow-up with her HCP and now was doing physical therapy with the face 2x a week. The right side of the face was still not completely back to normal at this point.  Company comment:  This case concerns a 60 year old female, with no medical history reported, who experienced  Serious ( Medically Significant )  , expected  event of Bell's palsy and other non-serious events which occurred on an unknown date with the 2nd dose of mRNA-1273 vaccine ( Moderna Covid 19 Vaccine ) . The patient was presented with 4 days of non-radiating RUQ abdominal pain worsening with fatty meals. His symptom started abruptly with associated nausea and non-bloody vomiting. In the emergency department RUQ ultrasound was performed which was significant for gallbladder sludge and the presence of a 2.3 cm stone in the gallbladder neck consistent with acute cholecystitis without dilated common bile duct (CBD). General surgery was consulted with a plan for non-emergent cholecystectomy. The patient was subsequently started on broad spectrum antibiotics coverage with ceftriaxone 1 g every 24 h and metronidazole five hundred milligrams every 8 h along with intravenous (IV) fluid administration. He was incidentally found to be COVID-19 positive on routine surveillance testing, but did not have any respiratory distress such as shortness of breath, pleuritic chest pain or changes in his exercise tolerance  Patient was incidentally found to be COVID-19 positive on routine surveillance testing, but did not have any respiratory distress such as shortness of breath, pleuritic chest pain or changes in his exercise tolerance.  Furthermore, he did not require any supplemental oxygen and previously received two doses of the Moderna vaccine. As the patient was asymptomatic, COVID-19 treatment (which included dexamethasone, remdesivir, and tocilizumab) was not initiated.  Patient was followed up as an outpatient post-surgery with improvement of his abdominal symptoms and his lab values normalized. The events occurred unspecified time the second dose of the mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 vaccine) . Reportedly, the patient presented with 4 days of non-radiating RUQ abdominal pain worsening with fatty meals. His symptom started abruptly with associated nausea and non-bloody vomiting. Ultrasound result was consistent with acute cholecystitis without dilated common bile duct (CBD). General surgery was consulted with a plan for non-emergent cholecystectomy. The patient was subsequently started on broad-spectrum antibiotics coverage along with intravenous (IV) fluid administration. He was incidentally found to be COVID-19 positive on routine surveillance testing, but was asymptomatic. On the day of surgery,the diagnosis of choledocholithiasis without cholangitis was made and ERCP was performed to relieve biliary obstruction. The authors considered the events as unlikely related to mRNA-1273 and possibly related to COVID-19. Rechallenge was not applicable since the event occurred after the second dose so, no rechallenge was done and recurrence was not applicable.  The benefit-risk relationship of drug is not affected by this report.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: severe tremors; aches; joint pain; 101.7 fever; chills; BNT162b2 dose 3 (booster); extreme fatigue; This is a spontaneous report received from a contactable consumer (patient). This consumer reported events after the first, second, and third dose of vaccine. This is the third of three reports (dose 3). A 69-year-old female patient received BNT162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number FF2590) intramuscular in left arm on 15Oct2021 01:00 PM (at the age of 69-year-old) as dose 3 (booster), single for COVID-19 immunisation. Vaccination facility type for third dose was reported as hospital or drug store. The patient did not received any prior vaccinations within 4 weeks. The patient's medical history included high blood pressure from unspecified date and ongoing. The patient's concomitant medications included valsartan/hydrochlorothiazide (HCT), oral from unspecified date and ongoing for high blood pressure. The patient previously received BNT162b2 (lot number EL3247), intramuscular in left arm on 18Jan2021 08:30 AM as dose 1, single for COVID-19 immunization and she did not experience any reaction other than a sore arm for a day or two. She also previously received BNT162b2 (lot number EL9264), intramuscular in left arm on 08Feb2021 08:30 AM (at the age of 69-year-old) as dose 2, single for COVID-19 immunization and by 10 PM (08Feb2021), she began experiencing chills, body aches, joint pain and 101.9 fever. This lasted for 4 days followed by 100-degree fever for another day and extreme tiredness for several weeks. In light of this reaction, she was hesitant to obtain a booster shot without discussing this with a professional medical adviser. Her concern was that this was not a typical response and that she was experiencing a hyperimmune or autoimmune response. Also, Guillain-Barre syndrome crossed her mind. At that time, she did not consider that the product was defective, but rather that something in her immune system might be amiss. On 27Sep2021, while at a well-care visit, she discussed this reaction with her physician. She recommended that perhaps she could delay taking the booster if she checked her antibody titers. She was not comfortable with putting off the inevitable, taking a booster, since she was over 65 years old. The following day, she called the facility to obtain reassurance that her reaction was normal and it would be safe to make an appointment for a booster shot. She spoke to (privacy) in the medical division. She advised her to speak to her physician which she had already done and she read off a list of common reactions. A small amount of vaccine leaked out from the arm of a 6 yo during administration of dose. I could not find guidance in the FDA EUA document, but the CDC interim clinical considerations guidance does address (last updated 11/19/21) and now seems to recommend more clearly to repeat the dose immediately for lower than authorized dose administered e.g. leaked out:  Lower-than-authorized dose volume administered of the correct formulation (e.g., leaked out, equipment failure, recipient pulled away): Repeat dose immediately (no minimum interval). See: https://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/covid-19/clinical-considerations/covid-19-vaccines-us.html. Based on this, spoke to family, reviewed the limited data available from the phase 1 portion of the Pfizer trial, both 10 and 20 mcg doses were overall well tolerated, though high fever did develop in one child after dose 2 of the 20 mcg dose, lasting 3 days. Since this patient has both an underlying urea cycle defect and periodic fever syndrome, risk of fever bears consideration due to a higher predisposition as well as potential risk of metabolic sequelae arising from fever- so the discussion mostly focused around this increased risk of fever/ reactogenicity. Parents had a chance to talk to his geneticist and discuss amongst themselves, weighed risks vs benefits, felt they could likely manage a fever if it developed by working closely with his genetics team and they ultimately desired to ensure optimal protection by vaccination. He returned to the clinic, and was re-dosed without event. We have not had any other reports of this. The nurse is a seasoned vaccinator so I would trust her vaccination method. It could be an issue with the syringe itself or a faulty syringe that was leaking around the hub.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 89 year old male with PMHx anemia, hypothyroidism, loop recorder, hyperlipidemia, Afib on Xarelto, Hx. of MI., DM, and HLD who presents to ED with a chief complaint of fatigue/weakness for the last 3 weeks. Patient presented to the ED, active inclusion cyst at the inferior border of the R Scapula, which was red and tender which he has been getting drained weekly by Dr. was given keflex, starting on Oct. 4, 2021, which he completed with no without improvement. Patient states he also received the Flu shot on 10/7/21 which he attributed to increasing his fatigue, and at that time began to have episodes of profuse diarrhea. When admitted, patient found to be COVID+-- but throughout his admission, patient was asymptomatic, and stable on RA. Completed Moderna vaccine in April 2021. On admission, labs were notable for: WBC: 5.4 with lymphopenia | Hgb 6.1, and thrombocytopenia | hyponatremia Na 129 | COVID-19 inflammatory markers: D-dimer: 899, CRP: 28.9, LDH: 265, Ferritin: 88. CXR: patchy airspace disease, L > R. UA unremarkable for infection. Patient was given 1L NS bolus, and 2U pRBCS -- which brought resolution to his anemia and hyponatremia. Anticoagulation was held 2/2 requiring blood transfusions and he was placed on IV Protonix BID for suspected GI bleed. Per ID, patient s/p monoclonal antibody infusion, and advised monitoring patient off of antibiotics at this time and continue local wound care (wet to dry dressing, per surgery). In regards to the suspected GI bleed, presenting Hgb level likely 2/2 blood loss from repetitive cyst I/D. Patient had endoscopy in October which revealed gastritis and hemorrhoids. Per GI, if patient's hemoglobin drops again as an outpatient patient will need repeat endoscopy and possible video capsule procedure. Patient admits improvement with fatigue with Hgb values stables, and is hemodynamically stable for discharge. Patient to restart baby aspirin 10/15/2021 and Plavix 10/20/2021 -- patient advised to stop Xarelto use at this time. Patient to follow up with his PCP within on week, and to repeat CBC Friday 10/15 and Monday 10/18, for further analysis.
LAB_DATA: Lab test positive for detection of COVID-19 virus

Received 1st injection in March. Had 2nd dose set up in 20 days but after 11 days was sent to hospital for throwing up and abdominal pain. Was diagnosed with full stones and pancreatitis. Had surgery to remove gull bladder. Sent home after a week but returned to hospital after 4 days with sepsis and put in icu. Had fever and tachycardia. Spent 45 days in hospital. Sent home with a thickened diet because had swallowing issues. After 4 days went back to hospital after throwing up blood and bile. Spent 2 months back in hospital with tachycardia and blood pressure issues. Had developed narcotic pancreatitis and had 2 more surgeries to fix a block in arteries. Put on vent twice and couldn?t get o2 levels regulated. Ended up with a Trach before going home with hospice and passing away 9 days later.

Hospital Course Patient is a 74 y.o. male patient who originally presented to the hospital on 11/15/2021 with history of type 2 diabetes, TIA, triple agent, Bell's palsy, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.  Presented with left-sided facial numbness.  He also has been recently tested for COVID due to family members with COVID symptoms.  Patient tested positive on 11/12.  He has been very anxious since he tested positive.  The patient is fully vaccinated.   Patient came to emergency department with hand left-sided facial numbness.  Someone thought he might have facial weakness but by the time he was seen in the emergency department, no facial weakness was noted.  Full neurological exam was normal.  NIH stroke scale was 1. CT of the head and MRI brain were negative for stroke.  Symptoms thought to be likely due to his Bell's palsy or anxiety.   Patient did received monoclonal antibody for his COVID infection.  He will be discharged to home today as he is back to his baseline.     Consultations During Hospital Stay: Neurology   REASON FOR CONSULT: Signs and symptoms of acute stroke     ASSESSMENT/PLAN: Patient is a 74 y.o. male with a history of Afib s/p Watchman device, HTN, HLD, T2DM, OSA on CPAP, Bell's Palsy with residual left facial droop, CHF, Asthma, Anemia, COPD and TIA who was recently diagnosed with COVID-19 on 11/12/2021. He presents to the ED on 11/15/2021 after developing sudden onset right facial droop and right facial numbness. LKW 11:00am, initial NIHSS 1.   Transient right facial droop Transient right facial numbness Symptoms completely resolved shortly after arrival to the ED. Given hypercoagulable state in the setting of COVID-19 infection, TIA is of high concern. Known Afib with watchman in place. With Echo completed within the past 3 months (9/7/2021), no need to repeat at this time. Plan: - MRI Brain without contrast - Daily NIHSS until stroke ruled out with MRI - Lipid Panel and A1c pending - Cardiac telemetry - q4hr Neuro checks - NPO until Bedside Swallow - PT/OT/SLP The above information was discussed with my attending physician.  Please see their attestation for further information.

On 11/19/21 Patient came in for her first Pfizer vaccine appointment.  Consent form was completed without questionable concerns for administration.  Patient was administered the Pfizer vaccine while seated in the pharmacy waiting area.  After the shot was given, I asked discussed reminder date for second shot, common side effects of vaccine, and asked her to remain seated in the pharmacy area for a little bit to make sure she was feeling alright.  While administering the next patient's vaccine in the pharmacy waiting area just a few minutes (2-3 mins) later, my back was facing Patient across the room and as I was speaking to the other patient, I heard a loud clunk hit the floor. I immediately turned around to see Patient collapsed on the floor in front of her chair. We immediately call 911 and the floor manager and I rush over to her and place her on her side and call her name to elicit a response.  She is responsive within about 15 seconds of calling her name.  She begins to talk normally while remaining on the floor with me on the floor beside her. I asked if she had ever had a reaction like this to a vaccine to which she said no but she has had fainting episodes in the past. A few minutes go by and she has called her father to come pick her up and shes seated in a chair.  The paramedics arrived and discussed with Patient her medical history, took vitals, and asked if she would like to go to the hospital.  Patient said no and I confirmed that her father would come to pick her up from the pharmacy.  As the paramedics are walking to the exit of the building, Patient fainted again and was quickly responsive again.  The paramedics came back over and got her buckled into the stretcher for transport to the ED.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Major fatigue and body inflammation which were exasperated with the second dose.  I have developed a major case of Lichen Planus, which indicates that my body has kicked into hyper immunity.  My mouth is full of sores, my gums bleed, rashes, my nails got wavy, I bleed in places I don't want to talk about, it takes me hours to get moving, I am uncomfortable 24/7.  It started about 3 weeks after my first Moderna.  I had my second shot months later and that's when I started to go very downhill.  Yesterday a doctor and I did a timeline and connected the dots.  I have begun an aggressive treatment of prednisone which in just one day has lessened the bleeding in my mouth.  Another note:  3 weeks after my first shot I kept trying to fight off what I heard is described as Covid Fog.  I got in a car accident for the first time in decades.  My blood pressure soared after the first dose from 135/82 to 200/100.  I am responding to a low dose of BP medicine which my GP feels will not be necessary once the LP is under control.
LAB_DATA: Since 3 weeks after the second dose I have visited multiple doctors since the symptoms are so varied. My GYN misdiagnosed issue as yeast infection.  Urgent care misdiagnosed  my mouth pain and bleeding as fungal infection.  Then the dentist identified it as Lichen Planus but topical oral ointment did not suffice and my condition continued to deteriorate. This past week I saw my GP who sent me yesterday to a skin specialist who identified it as LP, took a biopsy, put me on a high dose of prednisone and a stronger topical ointment for the many body parts impacted.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 69y.o. male with a past medical history the past medical history significant for BPH, hypertension, Alzheimer's dementia who presented on 10/12 for altered mentation. He was admitted for further workup and management. Mental status improved back to baseline with improvement of SBP. Antihypertensive regimen was adjusted accordingly. Neuro was consulted, low concern for seizure. HCT NAP. Patient was placed in isolation 2/2 covid 19 diagnosis. As he required no O2 there for management was supportive. At discharge patient will require specialty bed due to frequent changes in body position such as to alleviate pain, prevent aspiration or a respiratory issue which are not feasible with an ordinary bed. Additionally, he needs a specialty bed because he requires positioning of the bed to be elevated more than 30 degrees most of the time because of CHF, COPD, or problems with aspiration. He will also require a wheelchair as he has a mobility limitation that significantly impairs his/her ability to participate in one or more mobility related activities of daily living, such as toileting, feeding, dressing, grooming and bathing in customary locations of the home. Additional needs for a wheelchair include limitation cannot be sufficiently resolved by the use of a cane or a walker. The use of a manual wheelchair will significantly improve the patient's ability to participate in activities of daily living and the patient will use it on a regular basis in the home. He will be able to self propel with a wheelchair. Patient is stable for discharge to group home with hhc and instructions to start/continue/stop meds as specified below and schedule/attend all follow up appointments as specified below. He is to quarantine until 10/22/2021. Total time for discharge was in excess of 34 minutes.

Deceased 11/19/2021; Hospitalized 11/11/2021; COVID-19 positive 11/13/2021; fully vaccinated  BRIEF OVERVIEW: Admission Date: 11/11/2021 Discharge Date: Nov 19, 2021   DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: PRESENTING PROBLEM: Generalized weakness AKI (acute kidney injury) Altered mental status, unspecified altered mental status type Venous stasis ulcer of other part of left lower leg with fat layer exposed with varicose veins Venous stasis ulcer of other part of right lower leg with fat layer exposed with varicose veins Pneumonia due to COVID-19 virus COVID-19 AMS (altered mental status)   HOSPITAL COURSE: 90 y.o. male who presents today from assisted living with one week of progressive generalized weakness and AMS. PMHx of venous stasis ulcers on legs chronic, unhealable, CAD, HTN, pacemaker, PAF, CKD3, h/o PE and DVT on Eliquis. Patient was actually enrolled in hospice recently to try to achieve better pain control for leg ulcers, despite life expectancy being >6 months. He had been started on neurontin and hydromorphine, then the narcotic was changed to moprhine.  Patient has CKD. In the ED he was noted to be COVID+ but on RA.  He was admitted for further care.     Neurontin and narcotics were held and patient's mental status improved. Palliative care was consulted and began oxycodone for pain control. This was titrated up.  Initially patient remained on RA and was symptoms free with the covid19 infection. Repeat CXR was consistent with multifocal PNA and PCR confirmed covid +. Was offered monoclonal AB treatment but declined. On 11/14 patient began declining again with AKI and hypotension and worsening AMS. Lactic acid was normal, WBC 11.  CXR 11/14 showed new medial rt lung base opacities concerning for aspiration/PNA.  Unchanged lt opacities.  Blood cultures sent and zosyn given while ruling out superimposed bacterial infection. Given worsening renal function, despite patient not having had received narcotics in the past 12 hours, narcan was given with good response.  Narcotics held.  Patient was placed on IVFs and bolused. Starting on 11/14 patient began to have an O2 requirement and was started on Decadron. After initial narcan patient then had recurrent hypotension and sedation.  2nd narcan given with some response.  At this point discussion was had with daughter regarding goals of care. As patient was at the beginning of his covid course, which was likely to continue to worsen, having AKI, AMS, and then bleeding and severe pain from his chronic LE venous ulcers, We made the decision to pursue comfort care.  All aggressive interventions were discontinued and patient was started on comfort medications.  Hospice were consulted.      The patient was discharged home with hospice on 11/19/21.

Sunday cont to get worse but I could still manage to do life and by Monday at 7am I had to go to ER as the swelling continued and the pain intensified from trying to walk and move. I explain to the ER that I had received a Covid booster vaccine on Friday and did not see any immediate changes until Saturday night when I couldn?t get my rings off my fingers at bedtime. I continue to experience swelling throughout Sunday and by Monday I couldn?t walk without pain or move without pain. The ER monitored my blood pressure which was extremely high 250/112 ( exact measure  avail on ER report). They ran a blood lab and EEG which our normal gave me a starting dose of prednisone and sent me home with a prescription for four additional doses of prednisone. They told me it was going to take at least three days before the swelling went down. I have had to call out for work as I am a physical therapist assistant and cannot return to work until I can safely manage patients in my nursing home. I have a follow up appointment with my PCP on Tuesday, November 30 to address the concerns with the high blood pressure and to continue to monitor the swelling .

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Deceased 11/17/2021; Hospitalized 11/10/2021; COVID-19 positive 11/10/2021; fully vaccinated  BRIEF OVERVIEW:  Admission Date: 11/10/2021   DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: PRESENTING PROBLEM: Acute respiratory failure [J96.00] COVID [U07.1] COVID-19 [U07.1]   HOSPITAL COURSE: Patient is a 57 y.o. female who initially presented on 11/10 for 3-4 days of worsening shortness of breath, diarrhea, and nonproductive cough.  She had pitting edema and signs of fluid overload on CXR and was diagnosed with COVID on arrival.  She is on 5 L oxygen at baseline and was started on high-flow nasal cannula and initially admitted to hospitalist service.    She was diuresed aggressively. She was started on steroids; did not qualify for Remdesivir due to kidney function.Her oxygen requirements continued to increase and she was transitioned to 100% high-flow nasal cannula with non-rebreather mask. Overnight on 11/11, she desated into low 80s and was placed on BIPAP and transferred to ICU service due to concern for impending intubation.    Her respiratory status declined and was intubated on 11/13.  We had multiple conversations about her likely poor prognosis considering her baseline respiratory status, and patient elected to proceed with intubation at that time.  She was sedated and paralyzed, and she subsequent required initiation of norepinephrine. Her respiratory status continued to worsen and we began proning on 11/14. She responded to proning and was continued on a 20:4 proning schedule.   Palliative care was consulted on 11/15 after family expressed concern about patient's grim prognosis and likelihood of tracheostomy and long-term care even if she survived this illness. On 11/16, palliative spoke with all first-degree relatives, and they decided to transition to DNR and comfort care. Paralytics turned off and patient pronounced dead on 11/17/21 at 12:45AM. Family at bedside, condolences offered.
OTHER_MEDS: acetaminophen (TYLENOL) 500 MG tablet albuterol (PROVENTIL) (2.5 MG/3ML) 0.083% nebulization ALBUTEROL 108 (90 Base) MCG/ACT inhaler aspirin 81 MG EC tablet atorvastatin (LIPITOR) 20 MG tablet busPIRone (BUSPAR) 15 MG tablet Calcium Carbona

On 10/2/21 I started having dizziness and vomiting along with nystagmus of my eyes, ringing and moderate hearing loss left ear.  I went to ER they diagnosed me with vestibular neuritis/labrynthitis on my left side. I continued to vomit for 7 days straight, unable to get out of bed, care for my kids or work.  I had double vision with my eyes open. I had 100% loss of balance, could no longer walk without falling down.  I started physical therapy at week 2 and have continue to do this weekly.  This has helped me recover enough balance to be able to walk again, though I still cannot run or do the sporting activities that I previously enjoyed.   I have 100% loss of function of the vestibular system in my ear on the left /side leaving me with permanent dizziness. I am unable to ride a bike, play sports, go up and down stairs unassisted and unable to perform my job of assisting in surgery.  I am dizzy every day all day and even walking is difficult.  I have 3 children that I now have difficulty caring for.  My adverse event was approximately 4 weeks after my injection.  I am now starting to receive the bills from this and now it is affecting me financially.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: Patient is a 84 y.o. female with history of paroxysmal atrial fibrillation on Eliquis, T2DM, hypothyroidism, hyperlipidemia, aortic valve replacement HFpEF, OSA, CKD 3, and iron deficiency anemia who presents as a transfer from another hospital after a cardiac arrest.  Patient was in the outpatient surgery clinic receiving an iron infusion today when she suddenly began to feel nauseous.  She then became unresponsive.  A respiratory therapist checked for pulse and could not find 1 so CPR was started.  After roughly 1 minute of CPR, she started yelling, her pulse was checked and heart rates were in the 60s.  She remained alert and oriented since this incident. Per report she was incontinent during the episode.  She has been awake and alert since this incident.  She continues to feel nauseous.  Prior to the event she denies any chest pain but since CPR she has external musculoskeletal chest pain with any sort of movement of her upper body.  Of note she tested positive for COVID-19.  Per outside records her daughter presumed she had COVID around November 2nd and her symptoms, including a slight cough resolved about a week later.  She was never tested at that time.

My joints, knees, hips, shoulders, and neck were all hurting. When I tried to sit it would hurt. I couldn't barely get out of bed because of the pain. I took a bath one night and couldn't get out of it because of the pain. I went to my doctor, and she prescribed pain and anti-inflammatory medicine.  I see a rheumatologist. I had inflammation of 186 when the normal range is 15 to 30. I was very inflamed, so the doctor started me on prednisone 80mg, and then she added in a methotrexate medication. She was trying to reduce the prednisone dosage but when she does my symptoms would come back so she would have to bring it back up. I was diagnosed with polymyalgia rheumatica. I'm still having pain in my hips and knees while still on medication. I will be on medication as long as I have it because if I stop it comes right back.

I was recovering from back surgery on 1/27/2021. By July I was able to walk up to three miles without problem.  I noticed weakening in my legs in early August and was barely able to walk at all by mid-August.  I began using a walker and saw my back surgeon, Dr.  mid-September.  By then I had fallen several times and was using a wheelchair to get around.  Dr. suspected Guillain-Barr syndrome and referred me to MD, a neurologist.  After about a month, I went back to using my walker and by the beginning of November, I was able to walk unassisted, though with weakness persisting in my legs.  I began Physical Therapy 11/11/2021.  I continue to improve slowly, though still have quite a bit of weakness in my legs.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1. Vaccine reaction, initial encounter      Discharge Instructions    As we discussed, I do think that this is a localized reaction and immune response to the vaccines that you received on Wednesday.  This does appear to be resolving.  I have outlined the area of inflammation today please look at this once per day.  If you have redness that is spreading outside the marked area especially if you have any red streaking running up or down your arm, or if your symptoms worsen again such you have return of fevers body aches, chills etc. this may indicate a developing infection and antibiotics may be needed.   You may take acetaminophen and/or ibuprofen if needed.  I do recommend trying to keep your arm elevated at least at heart level when at rest.   Please advise your primary care provider of the reaction.     Differential diagnosis considered include local reaction to vaccine, cellulitis.   Patient notes that he was experiencing symptoms of body aches, malaise fatigue and fever the symptoms have all resolved.  He states initially he did not notice the redness and first noticed this yesterday.  He states that it did seem to be more swollen yesterday but has improved today.   Patient does have an erythematous area with well-defined edges, this area is warm to palpation not hot and swelling is very mild at this point.  As patient describes symptoms of improvement I do think that this is a local immune response to either the shingles vaccine or the pneumonia vaccine both of which she received in the same arm.   At this time I do not think that this is a cellulitis and did not recommend for antibiotics.  The area was outlined with date and time.  Patient is to monitor to the area and return if he has worsening redness including red streaked or worsening symptoms such as fevers, chills or body aches returning.   I did recommend that he contact his primary care provider and advised them of the reaction.  Aftercare follow-up and return precautions reviewed he verbalized understanding is agree with this plan.   This document was made with voice recognition software.  Although every effort was made to edit the content, transcription errors may occur.
