SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 9/1/2021 at about 5:30PM, I started feeling congested and had a runny nose and a scratchy throat. I went to bed early. The runny nose continued to 9/2/2021, on which day I also woke up with a mild headache. When I got up, I took some Tylenol and then read my temperature, which was about 99 degrees. I then called my employer, told them I thought I had a cold, and told them that I wouldn't be at work that day. I slept most of the day that day, and I gradually realized that it might not be a cold, but COVID19. I then called Dr. and arranged a drive thru COVID19 test on 9/3/2021. On 9/3/2021, I was tested for both COVID19 and strep throat, and I tested positive for both. Dr. phoned in a prescription for antibiotics. I also received a call from Dr. at Urgent Care, and she informed me that I qualified to receive an infusion of monoclonal antibodies and asked me to come in straight away, which I did. After getting the antibody infusion, I came home and stayed there 10-12 days. I began working from home 9/16/2021 or 9/17/2021. By then, all of my symptoms had subsided, except I had a persistent cough. I did not want to return to my workplace while I had the cough. I was finally able to return to my workplace on 9/20/2021.
LAB_DATA: On 9/3/2021, I had underwent a test for COVID-19 and strep throat at the drive-thru at Mercy Medical Group, and I tested positive for both.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt is a 90 year old MALE with pmhx of HTN, HLD, chronic  kidney disease Stage III who presented to ED 11/13 for worsening shortness of  breath and recent hx of hemoptysis. Patient states that he began experiencing  shortness of breath last night while sitting watching TV. He began coughing up  bright red blood per patient and witnessed by multiple family members. Denies  sputum production. Denies headaches, chest pain, abdominal pain, N/V, dysuria.  Patient was ultimately brought in to ED 11/13 for evaluation. Of note, patient  received 2 doses Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine in March/April 2021. Per CPRS records,  patient was exposed to Covid-19 shortly after Labor Day, in a group setting with  multiple family members. He tested positive for Covid-19 9/24, and was treated  at home with Regeneron c/b PE (diagnosed on 10/6, requiring hospitalization for  2 days). During 10/12-24 hostpial stay, patient presented with hypoxemia,  dyspnea, and chest/back pain 2/2 large right pneumothorax. Ultimately, he became  s/p pigtail catheter placement by IR x2 with complication of exudative right  sided pleural effusion and persistent volume loss on right side with right sided  tracheal deviation. His previous CT Chest on 10/18 and 10/16 showed  consolidative opacity in RML and RUL likely related to inflammation/fibrosis  which is causing volume loss. Patient is currently now on Eliquis 5mg BID. His  CT scan on 10/23 showed right mediastinal shift, suggestive of  inflammmation/fibrosis and blebs on right lung possibly suggestive of right lung  volume loss, and extensive chest wall emphysema in left lung. Patient ultimately  underwent follow CT scan on 11/1, which showed resolution of apical and basilar  pneumothorax, with posterior right lung concerning for infiltrates (vs. previous  fibrosis) with consistent extensive chest wall emphysema in left lung.   At admission, BP 123/74, with tachycardia (127). It was documented in ED that he  was initially at 91% pulse ox; however, very soon after, patient was found to be  satting at 55% on pulse ox, unable to give full history. Patient was placed on  NRB 15Lm ultimately satting at 97% on pulse ox. Chest x-ray at admission showed  small bilateral pleural effusions and extensive bilateral lung opacities, right  greater than left, increased since prior comparison study. CT thorax showed  enlarging, large right pleural effusion with new small left pleural effusion;  new multifocal septal thickening with groundglass opacity of both lung, highly  concerning for multifocal pneumonia, new fat stranding about the pancreas,  incompletely visualized concerning for pancreatitis. Patient noted to have a  heart rate initially 150 range; EKG showed sinus tachycardia. Patient  subsequently improved with IV fluids. However, given recent complex hx and  tenuous nature of his oxygenation after multiple attempts to deescalate his  oxygen in ED from NRB to Oxymask (patient will sat down to high 80s), patient  was admitted to ICU for stabilization and management."

Within a few days (at least by 9/6/2021) patient began to have fever and a cough.  Patient began to progressively decline.  Started with inability to ambulate.  At baseline patient could ambulate independently in her assisted living room.  Within days, she was no longer able to do so, her swelling worsened, and her oral intake declined.  This time period was complicated by an elevated potassium that improved with oral hydration and it was rechecked and improved, but her decline continued.  She was treated for a UTI from a gathered urine sample starting 9/7/21, but there is uncertainty to the extent it was either responsible or contributing to her declining status.  Patient was carried to the office on 9/16/21.  She was found to have an oxygen saturation of 79-81% on room air, she was too weak to hold her head up, and her swelling had increased.  EMS was recommended for transport to the hospital and with some convincing with her son's assistance, she finally agreed.  Patient was transferred from the rural hospital to a tertiary center in city.  She became severely oliguric.  She was given IV furosemide that was not very effective.  Patient was not only volume overloaded but also hypotensive requiring ionotropic treatment.  Renal failure worsened and nephrology opinioned that she was a poor candidate for dialysis given her poor clinical condition and recommended hospice care.  Patient died three days after admission on 9/19/21.  Inpatient team determined that urinary tract infection did not appear to be septic in nature.

I was 7 weeks and 5 days pregnant when I got the flu vaccine. I have had 2 live births and 1 miscarriage (at 5 weeks, 4 days) prior to this pregnancy.  The first live birth was a 5 lbs, 12 oz girl, full term, 24 hour delivery. The second was a 6 lb 0 oz girl, full term, 3 hours delivery.  I have had COVID-19 but not had the vaccine. My last period for this pregnancy was  Sept 4, 2021. I was 7 weeks and 5 days pregnant and at my first obgyn appointment when I got the flu vaccine. I had an ultrasound on this visit and the baby was showing healthy and exactly on track, growth-wise. Heartbeat was healthy. At the very end of the appointment, I got the vaccine. I had been having morning sickness for the previous two weeks. I had nausea all day, every day (including night time), and aversion to smells and most foods. The day after the vaccine, all nausea and smell/food aversions went away completely for 8 days. I was worried that I may be having another miscarriage. After 8 days, all nausea and food/smell aversions returned just as before. I was also particularly tired in the few days after the flu vaccine. I wanted to report this side effect because the sudden loss of pregnancy symptoms was startling.

Hospitalized 11/10/2021; COVID-19 positive 11/10/2021; fully vaccinated  Admission Date: 11/10/2021 Discharge Date:  11/18/2021 Admitting Physician:  MD Attending Physician:  MD Discharge Clinician:   MD Primary Care Provider at Discharge: No primary care provider on file. Hospital Course:    Pt is a 69 y.o. female with PMH of Non-ischemic cardiomyopathy EF 35%, DM type 2, CKD3, and GERD. She was hospitalized at BW on 11/10 concerning for hypoxic respiratory failure secondary to COVID19 pneumonia. She has been vaccinated.   Onset of symptoms were on 11/5. Patient tested positive on 11/10.    Initially hypoxic and requiring up to 2L of supplemental O2. Her Procal was normal. She was started on Decadron 6 mg daily and Remdesivir. Initial lab work up revealing for mild AKI likely pre renal and due to poor po intake which improved after gentle fluid hydration. Home diuretic held during hospital course and this should likely be resumed as outpatient. She is euvolemic on day of discharge. Similarly her home carvedilol has been hold for lower BP and HR in the 50's-60's. This can likely be resumed as outpatient. Her lisinopril is resumed on discharge.    Follow up CXR on 11/14 with predominantly right sided infiltrate which developed since 11/10. She was started on Rocephin and Azithromycin and completed 5 day course of therapy for CAP with improvement. She should continue dexamethasone through 11/20 given mild continued oxygen needs.    She has moderate protein calorie malnutrition and should continue with supplements. She refused subacute rehab placement and was established with home care services. Daughter is a former nurse and willing to take care of her, they will live together. Her diabetes is poorly controlled with an A1c of 9.3 and this should be followed up outpatient.    She was weaned to room air at rest with 2L oxygen with exertion and bedtime. CM assisted in establishing new PCP and safe discharge plan. Cardiology office will act as PCP until new physician established.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I have had Migraines all my life but since I got my COVID-19 vaccine I have been having more frequent and more severe migraines as well as problems with focus. It has been nine months and I have lost a lot of work. My migraines are triggered by smaller headaches which start. I am seeing a Neurologist and I have had an MRI. The headaches started about 3 months after getting the second dose of the vaccine. My migraines were controlled before and only happened a couple of times a month. They were easily controlled with medication. I started to get migraines 10-12 times a month and they are not easily controlled with medication. I was prescribed Inderal and I have to take 120mg as well as the medication that I used to take. Sometimes the medication does not work. I have extreme fatigue all the time and trouble focusing at work. I have had a lot of medication changes with no improvement. The headaches start at the back of my head and then move toward the front. My migraines were normally on the right side of my face and my jaw would ache. These are totally different, and they last for days sometimes. I have gone to Urgent Care and to the ER because the pain is out of control.

Hospitalized 11/10/2021; COVID-19 positive 11/10/2021; fully vaccinated  Discharge Provider: MD Primary Care Provider: PA Admission Date: 11/10/2021 Discharge Date: Nov 22, 2021 DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: PRESENTING PROBLEM: Hypoxia [R09.02] Acute hypoxemic respiratory failure due to COVID-19 [U07.1, J96.01] COVID-19 [U07.1]   HOSPITAL COURSE: This is a 57-year-old male who presented with weakness shortness of breath and fever to the emergency room on November 10.  He had had the Johnson & Johnson vaccine on October 22. Symptoms were present for 5 days prior to admission.  He had an outpatient COVID test at pharmacy which was positive.  In the emergency room his pulse oximetry was 86% on room air, and he initially was requiring 3 L of oxygen with a saturation of 93%.  Chest x-ray showed bilateral pulmonary infiltrates consistent with COVID.   He was treated with remdesivir and dexamethasone and nasal cannula O2.  He had Lovenox for DVT prophylaxis.  His oxygenation continued to worsen during his hospital stay and he was placed on high-flow nasal cannula oxygen which was required at an FiO2 as high as 90% with a flow rate of 50 liters/minute on November 15. After that he had gradual improvement and by discharge his oxygen requirement was from 6-10 L. in the 3 days prior to discharge he was treated with aggressive IV Lasix diuresis and high dose IV corticosteroids to try to improve his oxygenation, but had no affect.   He was discovered to have new onset asymptomatic atrial fibrillation on the day of discharge  which range with a heart rate ranging from 80s to 1 teens.  His blood pressure was only about 100 systolic, so the decision was made to do rate control with digoxin which does not cause hypotension.  He was also placed on Eliquis at discharge and was placed on an outpatient cardiac monitor for 14 days (ZIO patch) to determine how much atrial fibrillation he was experiencing.

Client received the 1st dose Pfizer COVID vaccine (lot# FK5618) in the L arm at 0935. After vaccination the client and his mother were seated in observation for 15 minutes. At approximately 0951 the client began to slump over in his chair and his mother slowly lowered him to the ground and asked for help. RN immediately responded to assess the client. RN removed clients mask, assisted in laying client in the supine position, and assessed a patent airway while RN took client's vitals. By the time client was assessed he was responsive to stimuli and his mother reported he was not responsive to stimuli for approximately 2 seconds. At approximately 0953 client was A&O x4 with no SOB and speaking in full sentences. Client vitals were BP 100/44 BP in the R arm laying down, HR 88, and RR 14. RN assessed client for injuries and observed no injury to the head or rest of body. Client appeared moderately diaphoretic. Client reported no pain, headache, numbness, tingling, or trouble breathing. At 1000 RN assisted client to the zero gravity chair. Client reported no dizziness when standing. Client was placed laying down in zero gravity chair. RN provided client with a water bottle, juice box, and graham crackers. RN observed client take sips of juice and finish his water bottle. Client ate graham crackers. Client reported he ate a waffle for breakfast and his mother stated that he has not had any water to drink.  At 1005 client's O2 saturation level was 96% and HR was 54. RN assessed strong equal grip, strong and equal pulses, cap refill <3 seconds, and skin warm and pink to touch. At 1006 RN advised client to remain in observation for 30 minutes and reviewed ER precuations with client's mother and advised to f/u with client's PCP. At 1007 client denied SOB, dizziness, nausea, headache, numbness, and tingling. Client reported "i feel Better now". At 1040 client left the vaccine with his mother and RN observed a steady and symmetrical gait.

I brought her and her son into an exam room to evaluate further.  on visual assessment and palpation, I could not discern any swelling of her face; L cheek felt just slightly warmer than R.  11:13AM  VS:  P 74, RR 18; sat 98%; BP 118/60 Pt continued to c/o L side of face feeling hotter and L eye getting "smaller".  Per son, he stated he thought her face was swelling; still not discernable to me.  Both other nurses also observed pt and did not feel her face was swollen.  When asked about request for prevaccination BP, pt denies being on any meds for BP; sates there is a family hx of high BP; states she "used to have BP but not anymore" 11:20AM pt continued to c/o swelling and eye closing.  With continued c/o; pt was administered 50mg Benadryl PO with her consent.  Pt sates she had not eaten so given water and graham crackers; advised that Benadryl may make her sleepy and cause her to have a dry mouth so encouraged to continue to drink. 11:30AM VS:  P 73; RR 18; sat 99%; BP 120/60. Pt sates face feels "calmer" and eye more open.  Pt appears less anxious; denies fatigue, dizziness 11:50AM  pt states she feels better, feels swelling has gone away and eye feels  fully open. VS P:  72; RR: 16; sat 97%; PB 116/62. 12:10PM  pt states she feels fine; denies fatigue and dizziness.  Advised to continue to drink fluids; if any further s&s to seek emergency care.  Advised to inform PCP of reaction at next visit.  Pt left with her son.

For two weeks following the initial Covid Vaccine, I experienced extreme emotional distress and an inability to regulate those emotions, I was unable to work for several days due to the amount of anxiety I was experiencing. I was incredibly anxious, depressed, and generally overwhelmed. I had many thoughts that were passively suicidal, and many emotions of self-hate and deprecation. I was able to gradually cope with these emotions and after nearly two weeks, the symptoms were gone.  I thought that this was due to stress buildup until i got my booster shot last Thursday (11/18/2021), Immediately after, my energy was completely drained, and the next day I was even more exhausted and started to feel incredibly anxious, and I decided to go to sleep as i was likely just tired. The next morning, I woke up to extreme fears of my friends leaving me along with a deep feeling of depression. The thoughts of self hate returned, but they only lasted a few days... I am still dealing with these symptoms but they have gotten better the last two days.
LAB_DATA: I do not have any medical records of these adverse effects, however I was in constant contact with my mother through both of these events - We have the Text logs and call logs, as well as banking records that could potentially be used as proof.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Right after I left the vaccine site my right arm began to hurt underneath. After a few minutes the site where I received the vaccine began to burn and I had shooting pain in my arm. As I continued to drive my arm began to spasm and my whole right side began to hurt. Suddenly after a spasm my hand closed and I could not get it to stay open. Soon after I could not feel my right foot. When I got home and got out of my vehicle I felt very dizzy and light headed and walking to my apartment was difficult. Once inside everything was spinning, my heart was racing and my chest felt tight, like I couldn't get a good breath. I then began vomiting. I had a temp of 99.8 later that evening. The next evening when I woke up, I still had the same symptoms. I called my Dr office and they told me I needed to go to the ER right away because of the extremity weakness. Patient was an 88 y.o. female with complex past medical history coronary artery disease, congestive heart failure, CKD, COPD narcolepsy, recent diagnosis of COVID19 on 11/06, who presented to the emergency department in cardiac arrest.   Pt arrived in cardiac arrest. Unresponsive with GCS of 3 and different exam as detailed in D/C . She was given another dose of epinephrine at time of arrival and given her shockable rhythm of Vfib pre-hospital, Doctor administered lidocaine. ACLS was continued with continuous chest compressions. Her first initial end-tidal that was obtained in the ED with 9. She was hypoxic at presentation to the 60s with symmetric coarse breath sounds bilaterally. Given the low end-trial and persistent hypoxia she was intubated. Tolerated well with no acute change. Following intubation, her oxygen saturations did temporally improved to the 90s and end-trial did temporally improve to 30; however, she remained pulseless, apneic, unresponsive and asystolic. Sodium bicarbonate was given as she was recently diagnosed with COVID-19 and concern for possible acidosis. ACLS was continued with continuous chest compression and pt. remained asystolic throughout her resuscitation in the ED. Family was available and was able to be with patient and was understandable and agreeable with termination of CPR given no ROSC after 60 minutes of resuscitation efforts. Time of Death was 12.53pm. on 11/17/20

Seen again at on 11/22, inguinal adenopathy decreasing in size, labs repeated including UA which showed microscopic hematuria.  At no time did she have fever. The second reaction in September occurred on my buttocks and resulted in swelling around into my groin, lymphadenopathy in my groin, and again, significant redness and hot to the touch.  This second reaction occurred within 24hours of the bite.  I was seen by Urgent Care clinic and received oral course of steroid therapy and antibiotics.  I have no known allergens to bites and have never developed reactions like this before.   I never saw the presumed insect that caused the bite but developed burning and itching sensation at initiation of both reactions.   Of note, after my second vaccine I did have axillary and clavicular lymphadenopathy on the 3rd day post vaccine that lasted for several days in addition to fever/chills 12h post vaccine, body aches, and fatigue.
LAB_DATA: No medical or lab tests performed

I had  the flu vaccine administered around 4:30Pm on 12/11/2020 at the clinic about a mile away from my house. By 7pm on 12/11/2020 my shoulder was in substantial pain? in an area towards the front of my shoulder, not the top/side where the guy at the pharmacy gave me the shot. I had my entire arm exposed during the shot (had a black long sleeve tee on and just pulled my whole arm out to make sure it was all exposed) and I found it odd that he was standing while I was sitting. Also, I said I wanted the shot in my left arm on my paperwork, but he administered the shot in my right arm. When he cleaned off the spot with alcohol to prep, he basically wiped a spot near my shoulder bone, at the top of my shoulder. I thought maybe he was just distracted and would make sure he sat down and confirmed the spot before injecting me. But he stood while administering my shot and injected really high on my arm in the same spot he cleaned, nearly at my bone. I?m 5?2?  and weigh about 100lbs and did not see the needle he used, but i assumed he would know what to use based on my size. I felt the prick of the needle and also some pretty unusual pressure when he was injecting me, and remember his hand was shaking pretty bad and he kept talking about the COVID vaccine while the needle was in my arm (which felt like a lot longer than usual). I didn?t have to sign anything and went on my way. Called my husband on the way home and said my injection didn?t feel right. I went to bed and woke up to excruciating pain toward the front of my shoulder, and I broke out in cold sweat due to the pain. I tried to move my arm to help with the stiffness, but it?s very painful. That next morning we both looked under the bandage at the injection spot and were surprised to see it Is nearly at the top of my shoulder. My pain worsened quickly. I could raise my arms or pick up my the. 9month old son.  It very scary and also painful. I had no shoulder issues before. I?m physically active and healthy. I received the flu shot in 2019 (at a clinic in my office building) and it didn?t cause any side affects. I have since had a cortisone shot and an MRI as well as PRP administered. The MRI shows I have a rotator cuff tear at the injection site as well as damage to the humeral head.  Dr administered PRP as a method to try to avoid surgery.  It is now more than 11 months since that vaccine and I still have daily pain with limited movement in my right arm.
LAB_DATA: Orthopedic surgeon appointment with x-ray ans Cortisone shot June 7, 2021 Physical therapy June 15, 2021 Ortho surgeon appointment July 22, 2021 MRI August 4, 2021 Orthopedic surgeon PRP injection August 17, 2021

Within one week of getting the second dose of the vaccine I thought I had a Canker Sore on my Tongue. It was on the left side, and it was elongated in shape. It got worse over time, and it started to spread down the left side of my tongue. I also had some white spots on my cheeks. The spots on my tongue were very painful. My doctor thought it was leukoplakia. I was referred to an Oral and Maxillofacial Surgeon. I made some dietary changes and it improved over the next 4-6 weeks. I was diagnosed with Oral Lichen Planus. I have never had anything like this before. It has been eight months and the condition has improved a little, but it is still there. It is smaller than it was, and it is only on the side of my tongue.
Breakthrough COVID

I had four days of adverse effects when I got the Moderna vaccine in April 2021. So I decided on the Janssen for my booster. My arm began hurting a lot almost immediately. By 8 p.m., I had a severe headache and took Tylenol, but it did not relieve the pain. At 11:30, I started throwing  up. After I threw up six times, my heart began racing, my fingers lost all feeling, my head felt like knives were stuck in it, and my ears were ringing with a staccato sound. I had 103.5 degree fever. I called the emergency room, and they said to come in if I continued to have these symptoms an hour later. My fever went down to 102 by mid-morning the next day, and finally to 99 degrees at 2:30 p.m. the following day. My head still hurts and I have a metallic taste in my mouth.
PRIOR_VAX: Moderna Covid vaccine April 2, 2021 (second dose) 4 days of adverse symptoms Age: 21

She was also hypotensive, noted to have extensive subcutaneous emphysema right chest tube was placed.  Patient was also in shock, thought to have cystitis.  She underwent a bronchoscopy which grew Enterobacter.  Due to persistent air leak, she underwent BAL on 10/29 with endobronchial valve placement in the right upper lobe.  Chest tube was removed on 11/06.  Patient was seen by infectious disease and they recommended Augmentin and ciprofloxacin for 3-4 weeks duration with follow-up CT scan.  Patient was discharged in stable condition.

On Sunday around 8pm patient got extremely tired before bed. This was unusual for him. He was falling asleep on the couch. He complained of a headache which he maybe only ever had once in his life. He wasn't running a fever. He woke up at 5:30am throwing up. It was almost all yellow bile. Took 2nd vaccine of Pfizer-BioNTech on May 10, 2021.  The day of the vaccine and time after, I didn't have any major symptoms other than low grade fever and fatigue. Starting Aug 16, 2021, starting seeing spontaneous urticaria (hives). These were happening daily for the first week or so and would regularly after that, but would be less often, maybe every 2-3 days. I took Benadryl or Claritin to treat the hives when I got it. I saw Doctor on Aug 18, 2021 and she recommended continue to take the antihistamines as needed and get blood work done for testing Basic Food Allergy and Upper Respiratory Allergy panel. All tests came back normal, I did not show any allergy to commonly tested food and environmental allergens. Nothing about my diet or environment has changed. And I have been working at home for the past 20 months. After the panel came back to be fine, i was referred to allergist at facility in city, I saw allergist on Nov 23, 2021 and told him about the Chronic Spontaneous Urticaria and a possible trigger of cold winds/temperatures. He has suggested I do urticaria screening labs to rule out any other possible systemic disorders. Up till now, I still get hives every 2-3 days and take antihistamines to resolve them. The hives always start on my thighs and travels to my lower legs, as well as up to the lower back. Rarely, it will show up on arms as well. I have no history of allergies and no other medical conditions prior to this problem.
LAB_DATA: Basic Food Allergy and Upper Respiratory Allergy panel (Aug 28, 2021) all came back <0.35 IgE Immunoglobulin E - Allergy Ranges 92.70 Immunoglobulin E - Basic Food Allergy Ranges 93.40
ALLERGIES: None and no history of allergies

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received his vaccine and sat down for his 15 minute observation period.  After approx 5 min of sitting, staff noticed patient was sweating profusely.  patient skin pale and clammy, very sweaty.  Patient stated he felt dizzy and his vision was blurry and he felt like he was going to pass out.  staff used an ammonia inhalant under patient's nose.  Cool papertowels applied to head.  Patient's mask and jacket were removed.  Patient given cold beverage.  Patient declined to lie on the floor.  BP 110/82, pulse 76 and regular.  Breathing normal, non labored.   staff sat next to patient for 15 minutes until patient stated he no longer felt he had to pass out.  Patient sat for an additional 15 minutes.  After 40 minutes of sitting, patient's color of face was no longer pale, skin warm to touch, no longer clammy and sweaty. staff stood next to patient as he stood from sitting position. patient stated he felt fine, no dizziness. Patient stated he was fine to drive himself home and he was going to go home and rest.

Received simultaneous flu and Pfizer Covid vaccine (3rd dose) on September 28. 30 hours later woke up with right thigh pain. Worsened over the next three days and evolved to include low back through knee. Essentially bed-ridden, unable to ambulate any significant amount without crutches or severe pain. Writhing in pain virtually around the clock. Associated numbness and weakness L3-L4. Rt hip film showed mild arthritis. PCP suggested physical therapy, with essentially no appreciation that I had gone from walking 6 miles a day/swimming/tennis to bedridden status. Lumbar MRI on day 19 showed bulging discs and stenosis ( worse on left -the "good" side) which I regard as old findings (please note I am a physician, board certified in /Internal Medicine and Radiation Oncology). Pain gradually started to subside at three weeks. Pain-free at 6-7 weeks. Numbness seems largely gone, now at 7 weeks.  My suspicion is that this was an inflammatory neuritis, presumably related to the Covid vaccine (acknowledging that a flu shot was given concurrently).

For in the emergency department, the patient was found to be hypoxic requiring 2 L nasal cannula.  COVID-19 PCR was positive.  Chest x-ray showed nonspecific left lower perihilar opacity.  The patient received Decadron in the emergency department and was transferred to Hospital for further evaluation.   The patient was treated with Decadron and remdesivir for COVID-19 pneumonia. She was seen by Rehab who recommended 4L NC with rest and 8L with oximizer with activity. PT recommended home with assist. She was discharged on decadron to complete course at home as well as given scripts for tessalon and guaifenesin. The patient was hemodynamically stable and all questions were answered at discharge.    Consults None   Procedures None

After vaccination felt fine other than sore arm.  At bedtime had mild chills and body aches.  Next morning I felt ok, had a headache, went to my physical therapy appt and couldn't do the exercises.  I tired very quickly.  I could do those exercises easily 2 days prior.  I went to work, felt malaise overall.  Felt better the next morning, mild headache - went to work.  I had been working on my feet all day for about 4 hours when I started to feel chest pain on the left side.  It was mild so kept working for about an hour or two.  I started to feel it on the left side of my back as well.  It started to get worse and I was starting to feel dizzy - I left work and went to ER. They did a bunch of tests to rule out all the bad stuff (heart attack, stroke, clots, etc).  All tests came back negative.  My blood pressure was higher than 180 when I presented at the ER and returned to normal after 3 hours at the ER.  Felt nauseated after the ER visit (assuming it was from the contrast dye injected during ER visit for CT scan).  Next day had overall malaise.  Still had chest pain but it was lessening.  Felt like the aftermath of something exploding in your chest and I was sore from the inside/out (vs outside/in when you workout - if that makes sense).  Minimally sore on day 4 and overall malaise - went to urgent care because I felt I should feel better by now.  Had a mild low grade fever of 99.4 (I normally run 98 or below and my 2nd covid vax elevated to 99.4 as well).  They tested me for covid (neg) and told me to give it a couple more days and come back if I still wasn't feeling well.  Day 5 felt more normal - was trying to check my blood pressure at home, but was consistently getting high readings - went to ER next day (urgent care refused to see me for high bp) - BP was only slightly elevated (127/92) - so suspect the high readings were false - as I felt normal that day.   I have history of mildly elevated bp in which I have controlled with diet/exercise last 2 years - no meds for it.
LAB_DATA: BW, chest x-rays, check CT angiogram, EKG - all 11/18/21
OTHER_MEDS: Ib profen, meclizine, women's multi-vitamin, calcium supplement, probiotic, zyrtec, birth control (seasonique)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 30 minutes after receiving the COVID-19 vaccine, my daughter started experiencing trouble getting a good breath. She was taking lots of deep breaths and holding her chest area. She said it felt tight like she couldn't breathe right. About 10 minutes later, she had a headache. She seemed very uncomfortable. I took her back to the hospital where she received the COVID-19 vaccine and they immediately walked us to the ER. Her blood pressure and oxygen levels checked immediately before taken back to a room. A doctor came in and suggested trying some Benadryl and just watching/monitoring her. About 30 minutes after receiving Benadryl, her headache subsided. Within an hour, her breathing was much easier. She was monitored for a total of 4 hours. During that time, her blood pressure was checked periodically and oxygen levels monitored.

When I woke up the next morning, I noticed multiple lumps (all under the skin) that were spread away from the initial injection site in addition to the original injection site. It gave me the impression the injection may have moved due to gravity (side sleeper). All of the lumps were painful, very red, and hot to the touch. My skin around the lumps was also red, and hot but less so. The redness continued to get bigger until Sunday (Nov 21st), which is when it started to show signs of fading. Currently my rash has faded some, but is still visible. It covers a large portion of my upper arm, and is around 6 inches around. I just felt horrible, but it was the chills that knocked me. The next day, the chills were starting to go away, the headache as well. Initially created November 18, 2021 *Updated 11/23/2021  On May 15, 2021, I received the one-dose Johnson and Johnson Covid-19 vaccination.   That day, I started my period, which I was expecting. After about 4 days, the bleeding started to become very heavy, and I expelled blood clots that were approximately the size of a racquetball. I have not experienced blood clots like this since I gave birth to my children. I have never experienced extremely heavy bleeding or clotting during my regular periods, which typically are spaced apart every 2-3 months. I contacted my OBGYN, Dr. approximately 2 weeks after receiving the vaccine. My doctor said that many other women had experienced changes in their menstrual cycles, and it may only last 2 months, so I decided to wait to see if this would be the case for me. It has not. Since May 15, 2021, I have been continually bleeding and/or spotting every single day. It?s November 18, 2021. 187 days have gone by (Update 11/23/2021: 192 days have gone by).    Since the bleeding did not subside after two months, I visited my doctor in person on August 30, 2021 to discuss options for controlling the bleeding. We agreed that an ablation would be the best route for me, since I am unable to take hormonal birth control, which is typically the first route of treatment for excessive bleeding, and I am no longer considering having more children. I am unable to take hormonal birth control because it exacerbates symptoms of my diagnosed Premenstrual Dysphoric Disorder (PMDD), which include anxiety attacks and suicidal ideation. All of this information, including my inability to take birth control due to exacerbation of PMDD symptoms, was documented by my doctor and sent to my insurance company for review and preauthorization. On October 15, 2021, I contacted Health Authority Management and spoke with a nurse who was handling the pre-authorization request sent in by Dr.?s office. I confirmed with her that my doctor had sent information regarding my inability to take hormonal birth control because of my PMDD, and reiterated this information, asking that it be taken into consideration for the preauthorization. The claim was denied on October 28, 2021. In that initial denial of preauthorization, it stated that a lack of clinical record of using hormonal birth control was one reason for the denial, which makes absolutely no logical sense, considering the aforementioned contact with Health Authority Management. Another reason given for the initial denial was that I had not undergone an endometrial biopsy to check for potential cancer. On November 12, 2021, my doctor performed an endometrial biopsy to ensure that I had a benign result for endometrial cancer. This was done in an effort to appease the other requirements of the insurance?s protocols, and to add to documentation for an appeal on my behalf. The results of the biopsy were benign. As of November 18, 2021, according to my doctor?s office, my insurance has again denied coverage for an endometrial ablation on the basis that there is no documentation that I have taken hormonal birth control as a first line of medical therapy. This is negligent, and a clear case of wrongful denial of a claim.   This condition, resulting from the Johnson and Johnson Covid-19 vaccination, has significantly inhibited my ability to function, and it is getting worse. On October 18-19, 2021, the bleeding was so excessive that I had to leave work early, and then miss an entire day of work. Starting on November 7, 2021, I began passing multiple, golf-ball sized blood clots per day. I am a middle school classroom teacher. I often have to have other teachers or aides supervise my class so that I can use the restroom to pass these blood clots. I feel physically fatigued, and have scheduled blood work to check for possible anemia and low ferritin (Update on 11/32/21: Dr.?s office received the results of my bloodwork, and it confirmed that I am in the beginning stages of anemia).  As of mid-November, I have begun to experience cramping in my lower abdomen, consistent with menstrual cramping. I cannot use tampons or my menstrual cup, because the excessive blood clots cause them to leak, so I have been wearing extra-absorbent, overnight pads, as well as disposable menstrual underwear (which is akin to wearing an adult diaper) every day. I am constantly worried that I am going to bleed through my clothing at work or outside my home. The constant wearing of pads and menstrual underwear has started to cause sores on my labia and the outer parts of my vagina, so simple movements like walking or sitting down/standing up can be very painful. These products are also not free; boxes of overnight pads are approximately $7.00 for 20 pads, and disposable menstrual underwear are approximately $7.00 for 7 pairs (I have to use multiple products per day, so one box of each of these products lasts approximately 5-7 days). On November 18, because of the secondary denial of coverage, which I knew would prolong the time in which I spent bleeding, and in an effort to reduce sores and chafing from disposable products, I purchased 2 pairs of washable period underwear, which cost me nearly $90.00. Physical intimacy in my marriage has been negatively impacted, especially as the bleeding continues to become heavier, and I become more physically and emotionally exhausted. To put it mildly, this has been humiliating. It is also taking a toll on my mental health. The constant anxiety about leaking, and worrying about my health is exhausting. In addition to all of this, if this procedure isn?t approved and performed by the end of December, I will have to incur the cost of my insurance deductible, which has already been met this year, so this will have a significant financial impact on me and my family. The continual denial of coverage for this procedure has left me feeling hopeless and angry. Every time I have used the restroom for the last 187 days (update 11/23/21 it has been 192 days), I am reminded of this awful side-effect from a vaccination I was encouraged to take, and hesitantly submitted myself to, believing that it was ?the right thing to do? for myself.   I wish I had denied taking the vaccine when I had the chance.

Her respiratory rate was 16 regular and unlabored, SpO2 97%, HR 80 and regular, BP 130/90 and she rated her chest pain a 4 out of 10 on the pain scale. She was alert and oriented x 4. The client was given a snack because she said she had not eaten in 3 hours. At 1019 the client said the numbness and tingling in her left hand/fingers was ?gone,? and the pain in her chest decreased to a 2 out of 10 on the pain scale. She denied difficulty breathing and said the feeling of ?indigestion? was going away.  Her RR was 15 regular and unlabored, SpO2 96%, HR 78 and regular, BP 138/94. She remained alert and oriented x 4.  Her color returned to normal, her skin appeared dry, and she appeared calmer. At 1022 the client said her chest pain was ?not as bad as before? and rated it a 1 out of 10 on the pain scale.  At 1024 the client said her chest pain was ?gone? and she no longer had numbness or tingling in her left hand/fingers. Her respiratory rate was 16, BP 134/86, HR 83 and regular, SpO2 96%. Her breathing appeared regular and unlabored.  She was alert and oriented x 4. RNs observed the client until 1033, then asked her to try standing up.  The client stood up without symptoms. She walked away with a steady gait and returned to work on site with her colleagues.  The client was educated to call 911 if symptoms resumed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Shot was at 11:30AM: I initially had pretty severe pain at the injection site that subsided about an hour after the shot.  1PM: I started having moderate shoulder pain. I could not lift anything or reach certain ways. The injection site not longer hurt, but my entire left shoulder did.  9PM: I developed a firm dollar coin sized lump under the injection site. This lump was hot to the touch and red in color. I drew a circle around the area to monitor growth. I also noted hive rashes in various parts of my body including the injection site, my right upper arm, my left eye, and my legs.  The next day, approx. 10:30 AM: injection site lump and rash had spread 1-1 1/2 inch from growth monitoring circle. Most hive rashes on the rest of my body started to go away. Shoulder pain still moderate, very noticeable. I was running a fever of 101.4 F.   9PM: Same symptoms as the morning. Took Benadryl per suggestion of pharmacist.   In the morning, the injection site lump and rash were still visible, but less. The shoulder paid was starting to fade slightly.   As of now, 11/23/2021 10PM: shoulder paid is barely noticeable. Slight lump under injection site and still a little warm to the touch, but nowhere close to what it was. Hives  have went away.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: SUSPECTED IMMUNOLOGICAL VACCINE FAILURE; This spontaneous report was received from literature: This report concerned a female of an unspecified age, race and ethnic origin. The objective of this study was to describe people with diseases or treatments that suppressed their immune system cannot count on the same protection most vaccinated people had. The patient's height, and weight were not reported. The patient had a rare concurrent condition, mucous membrane pemphigoid, which causes blistering of the gums and other areas. The patient was previously treated with the the steroid prednisone (drug used for unknown indication) in the past. She initially received two doses of the Pfizer vaccine (BNT 162) for prophylactic vaccination, but an antibody test revealed she had no response.  The patient received Covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, batch number: Unknown, and expiry: unknown) dose, start therapy date were not reported, 1 total was administered for prophylactic vaccination. The batch number was not reported. The Company is unable to perform follow-up to request batch/lot numbers. Concomitant medications included mycophenolate mofetil, an immunosuppressant drug often prescribed for organ transplant recipients. On an unspecified date, the patient again underwent antibody test which was negative. So, later she got three Moderna doses, after which she finally achieved a response similar to healthy people who have had two doses. The whole process lasted for six months. She quoted that "Her ordeal had contributed to approval of boosters for everyone but especially for immunocompromised people, boosters work and are needed!" The author emphasized on the awareness that must be created on how immunocompromised people without strong vaccine protection, are coping with Covid. The action taken with Covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The outcome of suspected immunological vaccine failure was not reported. SYMPTOM_TEXT: FIBROMYALGIA; CHEST  PAIN/FELT PAIN AS A BALL UNDERNEATH HER BREAST AND TO BACK/FELT INFLAMED; A BIT OF WATER/FLUID IN HEART OR LUNGS; ADVANCED PERICARDITIS; BACK PAIN; FALL; FEET HURT; RESPIRATORY INFECTION; This spontaneous report received from a patient concerned a 46 year old female. The patient's height, and weight were not reported. The patient's past medical history included: bacteria in intestine, and concurrent conditions included: fibromyalgia ,GI(gastrointestinal)issues, and penicillin allergy. The patient experienced drug allergy when treated with ranitidine hydrochloride.  The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, batch number:1805029, expiry: UNKNOWN) dose was not reported, 1 total administered on 17-MAR-2021 to left arm for prophylactic vaccination. No concomitant medications were reported.  After 3 weeks of vaccination, on APR-2021 patient developed respiratory infection and 2-3 weeks after that (5 weeks after vaccination as per consumer) on APR-2021, she developed a very strong chest pain radiating to back. On 11-MAY-2021 she visited her rheumatologist but he refused to treat her as she was experiencing really bad chest pain (consumer stated she was crying of pain non stop) and referred her to urgent care. She then went to emergency room, performed EKG(electrocardiogram) and found it to be normal and was sent home. However, that night she developed pain again and took acetaminophen with codeine, but pain was worst. She then went to another hospital, on 12-MAY-2021, where she was admitted for 2 to 3 nights. It was reported that she was also being followed up at that time for GI(gastrointestinal) issues and that all doctors overlooked her symptoms and attributed them to her fibromyalgia. The patient was discharged on 14-MAY-2021. The patient was hospitalized for 3 nights. The patient reported that she had the chest pain on and off since May and that all EKG she got were normal and doctors said it was just her fibromyalgia. The patient reported that she only went to emergency room and primary care physician for pain episodes, then stopped as they were not of any help. On 12-NOV-2021, she had a fall, and hurt her feet for which she went to emergency room (arrived passed midnight). On 13-NOV-2021, she had scans of her foot, and then complained of back pain. She had X-Rays of her back and then CT(computed tomography) scan of her chest was taken which showed pericarditis and fluid in lungs or heart (patient was not sure). We refer you to speak to your healthcare provider about the risks of the vaccine compared to the risks of potentially not being fully protected against COVID-19 infection. Fatal Multisystem Infl ammatory Syndrome in Adult after SARS-CoV-2 Natural Infection and COVID-19 Vaccination; After the second dose, he reported fatigue and malaise which resolved within 2 days.; After the second dose, he reported fatigue and malaise which resolved within 2 days.; This is a literature report.  Amultisystem infl ammatory syndrome in children (MIS-C) and adults (MIS-A) occurring after coronavirus disease (COVID-19) has been identifi ed; onset is 4-6 weeks after severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) infection. A case defi nition for MIS-A has been developed by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC); MIS-A after vaccination is rare and remains of great clinical and public health interest. We report a case study and histopathologic fi ndings from a fatal MIS-A case after SARS-CoV-2 infection and subsequent complete COVID-19 vaccination. The patient was a healthcare worker in his 30s with no notable medical history. In December 2020, he experienced mild COVID-19-like illness symptoms, including fatigue and loss of taste and smell. He did not undergo testing for SARS-CoV-2 at that time and was unaware of the need for isolation. Six days after onset of COVID-19-like symptoms, and when fully recovered, the patient received the first dose of Pfizer/BioNTech (https://www.pfi zer.com) mRNA COVID-19 vaccine. He received the second dose 20 days later. After the second dose, he reported fatigue and malaise, which resolved within 2 days. Twenty-two days after receiving the second dose of the COVID-19 vaccine, he had onset of new fever, malaise, headache, and odynophagia. He was examined by an outpatient medical provider. Diagnostic testing was notable for a negative COVID-19 test by reverse transcription PCR (RT-PCR), negative rapid influenza antigen, and negative rapid antigen detection for group A Streptococcus. Four days later, the patient visited an emergency department because of worsening symptoms. Assessment of vital signs revealed a temperature of 37.2C, heart rate 113 beats/min, and blood pressure of 117/66 mmHg. Physical examination identifi ed right-sided cervical lymphadenopathy, marked bilateral conjunctival erythema, and a faint papular rash on the pelvis and left flank. Laboratory testing revealed a peripheral-blood leukocyte count of 11,000 cells/ microL, 93.5% segmented neutrophils, and thrombocytopenia with a platelet count of 110,000/microL (Table). Portable chest radiograph results were without notable findings. On hospital day 2, the patient remained febrile and tachycardic (heart rate 90-135 beats/min) and had a blood pressure of 92/56 mmHg. Diagnostic evaluation revealed a negative SARS-CoV-2 RT-PCR test but a positive serologic test for SARS-CoV-2 nucleocapsid IgG. Additional diagnostic tests were conducted (Table). Inflammatory markers showed elevated C-reactive protein at 284.0 mg/L, serum ferritin at 1434.9 ng/mL, and troponin-I at 18.0 ng/mL. On the evening of hospital day 2, the patient received 75 g of intravenous immune globulin (IVIG). Early morning on hospital day 3, the patient had an acute change in mental status, including confusion and global aphasia. An emergent computed tomography scan of the head was negative for cerebrovascular accident and showed normal brain parenchyma and no evidence of acute infarction, mass, or hemorrhage. On completion of the scan, the patient was found nonresponsive and without a pulse. He underwent multiple rounds of advanced cardiac life support, resulting in return of spontaneous circulation. A chest radiograph showed an enlarged cardiac silhouette, and an echocardiogram showed severe biventricular dysfunction, severe global hypokinesis of the left ventricle, and left ventricular ejection fraction of 20%. The patient received a second dose of IVIg and intravenous steroids and extracorporeal membrane oxygenation support was initiated. On hospital day 4, severe multisystem organ failure continued to progress. The patient died on hospital day 4. We reviewed the patients medical history and clinical chart. We assessed serum samples collected during the hospital course before and after IVIg, and we determined endpoint titers to SARS-CoV-2 nucleocapsid (IgM and IgG) and spike receptor binding domain with neutralization functions against spike protein. The endpoint titer was a modified protocol. We completed an autopsy and sent formalin-fixed, paraffin-embedded tissues to CDC. Microscopic examination of lung, airways, pulmonary lymph node, liver, heart, spleen, kidneys and stomach tis sue samples was performed; LT-Gram stain was performed on lungs and heart. An RT-PCR assay for SARS-CoV-2 was performed on RNA extracted from formalin-fixed, paraffin-embedded tissues from lungs, airways, and heart by methods previously published. This activity was reviewed by CDC and was conducted consistent with applicable federal law and CDC policy. Serum antibody results drawn before IVIg infusion were negative for SARS-CoV-2 IgM but positive for IgG. Serum results had a high titer of anti-spike receptor binding domain antibody both before and after IVIg (1:75,000) compared with a naturally infected SARS-CoV-2-positive control (1:4,000). In addition, the pre-IVIG sample serum results demonstrated neutralizing function. Notable findings on gross internal autopsy examination included a 525-mL pericardial effusion and cardiac enlargement, as well as a 5-L hemoperitoneum and a 20-cm diameter perisplenic hematoma. Microscopic examination of the lungs showed diffuse congestion, increased intra-alveolar macrophages, multifocal hemorrhage, capillaritis, and microthrombi throughout. We observed no viral inclusions or diffuse alveolar damage. Trachea and bronchi showed mild tracheobronchitis. Sections of the heart showed multifocal myocarditis with mixed inflammatory infiltrate, myocyte necrosis, and numerous microthrombi. We also identified disseminated microvascular thrombosis in the heart, stomach, kidneys, and liver. Gram stain results were negative on lung and heart tissue. SARS-CoV-2 RT-PCR was negative on lungs, trachea, bronchi, and heart. Conclusions This fatal case of MIS-A occurred after full COVID-19 vaccination in a patient with prior natural SARSCoV-2 infection suspected 6 weeks before MIS-A symptom onset. Serum antibody results before IVIg infusion indicated the patient was previously infected with SARS-CoV-2 and was vaccinated with a COVID-19 vaccine. Antibodies to the nucleocapsid protein are the most sensitive target for serologic diagnosis for natural infection, and these antibodies are not present following COVID-19 vaccination alone. In addition, clinical history was compatible with natural infection beginning 6 days before the first mRNA vaccine dose and consistent with negative SARS-CoV-2 nucleocapsid IgM on testing during hospitalization. The patient demonstrated similar clinical findings to previously reported MIS-A cases, including fever for 3 consecutive days, laboratory evidence of inflammation, neurologic and mucocutaneous clinical findings, and severe cardiac illness that included systemic hypotension progressing to cardiogenic shock. These criteria meet the CDC case definition for MIS-A, as well as a definitive case at level 1 of diagnostic certainty by the Brighton collaboration case definition for MIS-A and MIS-C. In addition, the histopathologic findings of capillaritis and multiorgan microvascular thrombosis in association with clinical symptoms and laboratory findings are compatible with MIS-A. Substantial blood loss on gross examination may represent a diffuse intravascular coagulation-type picture in which diffuse microthrombosis depleted platelets and clotting factors. The etiology for clinical deterioration was likely multifactorial, although considerabl cardiac compromise in the setting of high fluid volumes and intraperitoneal hemorrhage may have contributed to multiorgan failure Whether mRNA COVID-19 vaccination contributed to MIS-A onset in this case is unclear, and future epidemiologic studies are needed to understand whether an association exists. The immunopathology leading to hyperinflammation causing MISA after SARS-CoV-2 infection remains unknown, although postinfection immune dysregulation is consistent among reported cases. Notably, MIS-A has not been reported among adult participants of COVID-19 vaccine trials, and no direct evidence exists to support vaccine alone as the primary etiology in this case. This article further emphasizes the importance of COVID-19 prevention, for which infection prevention strategies and vaccination remain our greatest defense.   Table. This Nurse reported for a 65-years-old male patient who received bnt162b2 (Pfizer COVID 19 Vaccine, Solution for injection, Batch/Lot Number: EW0217, NDC number, Expiry Date: Unknown) via an unspecified route of administration in right arm on 10Nov2021 (age at vaccination: 65-years-old) as dose 3 (booster), 1.8 ml single for COVID-19 immunisation. No medical history (The patient denied medical conditions) and no other products were reported. Historical vaccine included bnt162b2 (Pfizer COVID 19 Vaccine) on 11Feb2021 as dose 1, single and dose 2 taken on 11Mar2021; both doses taken for COVID-19 immunisation. Reporter did not have any information about the patient's other two doses of the vaccines except for the dates. Reporter stated that she had never drawn up the vaccine before and did not read the instructions carefully. She did not use a flashpoint needle, but a regular needle and syringe. She diluted the purple cap Pfizer BioNTech Covid-19 vaccine vial with 1.8 mL of diluent, then drew up the entire vial and administered it as the booster dose to the patient. Stated that the patient was a 65-year-old male, and it was his booster dose of the vaccine. Reporter further stated that they had never drawn up a vaccine on their own and did not use a flash point needle to do so. The vaccine was diluted properly but the entire vial was administered to the patient. The overdose only happened yesterday (10Nov2021), and the patient has only reported a sore arm (on an unspecified date in 2021) so far. She was asking for information on that administration error. Reporter declined to provide patient's initials, name, date of birth, height, weight, or ethnicity, she was not comfortable providing any patient information. Reporter also declined to provide her mailing address, alternative phone number, or fax number. When probed for specific seriousness criteria for the patient receiving the entire vial of the vaccine the reporter replied only with no. The reporter was not comfortable providing more specific patient details or practice address, and provided her manager contact information to speak to for future follow up. Reporter denied labs, testing, No Investigation Assessment was there, and she denied treatments taken by the patient for these events. The outcome of the event "The overdose only happened yesterday, and the patient has only reported a sore arm so far" was unknown.  No follow-up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: pharmacodynamic interaction between methotrexate, rituximab and tozinameran was considered; Brain death; COVID-19 pneumonia; systemic lupus erythematosus, had been receiving treatment with rituximab, methotrexate 25mg per week; This is a literature report.  A 60-year-old woman developed brain death secondary to COVID-19 pneumonia following concomitant administration of methotrexate, rituximab and tozinameran [routes not stated; not all dosages and outcomes stated]. The woman, who had a medical history of hypertension, type II diabetes mellitus and systemic lupus erythematosus, had been receiving treatment with rituximab, methotrexate 25mg per week and unspecified steroids. She had also been receiving apixaban for atrial fibrillation. On 02May2021, she presented to the hospital with fever (maximum temperature 104 degree F) and productive cough for a duration of one week. She had been vaccinated with tozinameran [Pfizer] for prevention of COVID-19 disease and received the second dose of vaccination on 18February2021. On 01April2021, she underwent routine COVID testing. At that time, she was tested positive; however, she was asymptomatic. On 24April2021, she developed productive cough and fever. Therefore, she was presented to the hospital. On day of hospital presentation, the polymerase chain reaction (PCR) testing for COVID-19 was found to be positive. Based on the clinical presentation and laboratory findings, COVID-19 pneumonia was considered. Therefore, the woman was admitted to the hospital on 03May2021. On hospital admission, her therapy with methotrexate was stopped and severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) antibodies were found to be negative. On 09May2021, she was admitted to the ICU due to acute hypoxic respiratory failure. Therefore, she received a complex course of treatment including unspecified broad spectrum antibacterial antibiotics, remdesivir and high-dose unspecified steroids for prevention of lupus flair. During the initial 5 days of hospitalisation, she continued receiving apixaban therapy, which was subsequently stopped due to the development of disseminated intravascular coagulation. On admission day 13, an altered mental status was observed, and she also reported headache. Subsequent head CT revealed a new acute to subacute infarct involving the right frontal operculum and insular region, new parenchymal haemorrhage versus haemorrhagic infarct involving the left parietal lobe and left cerebellar hemisphere and multifocal acute subarachnoid haemorrhage. The CT angiogram of the head and neck showed no definite evidence of an acute large vessel intracranial arterial occlusion or substantial arterial stenosis; however, multifocal irregularity within the superior sagittal sinus with sinus venous thrombosis were noted. The brain MRI performed on the following day showed acute left middle cerebral artery territory infarct and evolution of right frontal lobe infarcts on diffusion weight imaging. The contrast-enhanced venogram showed non-occlusive superior sagittal sinus thrombosis. After interdisciplinary discussion with haematology, neurosurgery and neurology, the woman was treated with heparin drip. On admission day 19, head CT showed continued expected evolution of infarcts with sulcal effacement surrounding the dominant left sided infarcts and trace rightward midline shift. On admission day 35, final head CT revealed cessation of contrast opacification of the anterior and posterior intracranial arterial circulation as well as new cerebral oedema with effacement of the gray-white matter borders, sulci, ventricles and cisterns, haemorrhage in the right frontal and left frontoparietal lobes at the site of previous infarctions, and new hyperdensity in the sylvian fissures consistent with subarachnoid haemorrhage. Based on the clinical presentation and laboratory findings, brain death secondary to COVID-19 pneumonia following pharmacodynamic interaction between methotrexate, rituximab and tozinameran was considered. Additionally, acute cerebrovascular disease was considered. Subsequently, she died due to COVID-19 pneumonia.  Pfizer is a marketing authorization holder of Rituximab and Methotrexate Sodium in the country of incidence or the country where the product was purchased (if different). This may be a duplicate report if another marketing authorization holder of Rituximab and Methotrexate Sodium has submitted the same report to the regulatory authorities.; Sender's Comments: Based on a temporal association and known product safety profile, a causal relationship between the reported events and suspect drugs were  assessed as possible. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to RAs, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.; Reported Cause(s) of Death: Brain death; COVID-19 pneumonia; pharmacodynamic interaction between methotrexate, rituximab and tozinameran was considered

SYMPTOM_TEXT: recurrence of acute myocarditis; recurrence of acute myocarditis; This is a literature report.  Author describe a case of an adolescent male patient who had recurrence of acute myocarditis temporally associated with receipt of a second dose of the PfizerBioNTech mRNA COVID19 vaccine. Case Presentation: A 17-year-old male adolescent with no significant medical history came to medical attention in Jan2021 with chest pain consistent with myocarditis. Serum troponin level peaked at 506 ngmL normal < 0.04 ng/mL. Cardiac magnetic resonance imaging (cMRI) showed 2 small areas of delayed gadolinium enhancement of the left ventricular myocardium. Electrocardiogram (EKG) showed diffuse ST segment changes. Respiratory viral pathogen panel polymerase chain reaction (PCR) testing including severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 SARSCoV2 as well as SARSCoV2 nucleocapsid IgG and IgA was negative. He received supportive care and was discharged after 6 days of hospitalization with normal cardiac testing including serum troponin, EKG and echocardiogram at 2week follow-up. On 15Apr2021 he received his first dose of the PfizerBioNTech COVID19 mRNA vaccine without any side effects noted. One day after receiving the second dose of the PfizerBioNTech COVID19 mRNA vaccine on 07May2021 he developed fever T max 101.3 degree F and body aches that responded to acetaminophen. The following day he developed sudden onset of severe burning left sided chest pain that radiated to the left shoulder and the upper left arm. He reported that the chest pain worsened with exertion and movement and was similar to that experienced during his previous episode of myocarditis. He denied any other symptoms. The patient presented to our emergency department hemodynamically stable however EKG revealed diffuse ST-segment elevations. Initial laboratory test results showed a serum troponin of 23 ng/mL , C-reactive protein of 29 mg/L normal 05 mgL and erythrocyte sedimentation rate of 5 mmh normal < 15 mmh. Respiratory pathogen panel PCR testing including SARSCoV2 was negative. SARCoV2 nucleocapsid IgG and IgA were negative and SARSCoV2 IgM antibody for the spike protein was positive consistent with recent immunization. Rheumatologic testing including antinuclear antibody test and rheumatoid factor was negative. He was admitted to the pediatric intensive care unit for telemetry and observation Initial echocardiogram revealed normal biventricular systolic and diastolic function and no evidence of regional wall motion abnormalities or an effusion. Telemetry revealed occasional isolated premature ventricular contractions. Troponin peaked at 51.37 ngmL cMRI showed low normal left ventricular ejection fraction 53% trivial pericardial effusion and subepicardial late gadolinium in the same distribution as seen in the previous episode but with interval increased enhancement. His chest pain improved with nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug treatment and supportive care and he was discharged after 6 days of hospitalization. At the time of discharge his troponin was 0.17 ngmL and EKG findings were normal At an outpatient cardiology visit 3 days after discharge the patients cardiac evaluation including EKG and echocardiogram was normal. Our patient had his first episode of idiopathic acute myocarditis 4 months before recurrence This recurrent episode of myocarditis may have been triggered by the vaccine administration through an autoinflammatory or autoimmune phenomenon Cardiac MRI during both illnesses demonstrated enhancement after gadolinium administration in the same distribution during both episodes. This case highlights the possibility that the COVID19 mRNA vaccine may trigger recurrent acute myocarditis in children and adolescents who have had a previous episode of acute myocarditis.  No follow-up attempts are possible; information about lot/batch number cannot be obtained. No further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information provided, the contributory role of the suspect product BNT162B2 to reported events myocarditis/disease recurrence cannot totally be excluded. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

Dizziness / apparent vertigo: First noticed during my bike ride to work, around 25 minutes into the 30 minute ride.  When I was about to resume riding after stopping at a stop light, I felt unsteady and dizzy to the point of nearly blacking out momentarily, but it subsided as quickly it started and I made it to work unscathed.  Throughout the day, if a tilted my head to either side, I would feel unsteady, but I was able to work relatively normally (but attempted to keep my head as straight as possible).  I attempted the Epley maneuver toward the end of the morning; I didn't experience nystagmus during the first step, but seemed better for at least an hour afterwards before it came back (though it remained mild).  The next day, Saturday, I initially thought the problem was over, but while I was at work, I had several brief episodes, but again, tried to keep my head straight and didn't experience any problems during the bikes to and from work.  On Sunday, the problem was intermittent at work.  I continued to try to keep my head straight.  On Monday, I had one intense episode in the morning after getting out of bed and entering the bathroom, but no others , though I tried to keep my head as straight as possible during my work-day.  I had no episodes today, Tuesday.
OTHER_MEDS: Duloxetine, Levothyroxine, Multivitamin, Calcium supplement, fish oil supplement, Tylenol several hours after vaccine
PRIOR_VAX: One day of intermittent vertigo-like experiences several weeks after my second Moderna.  I didn't link it with the vaccine at th

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 03/25/2021 at around 11:15am, I received my first Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine at the medical center. The vaccine came from lot number ER2613. The rest of the day I had zero symptoms as well as no soreness in my arm from the shot. On 3/26/2021 I woke up and felt completely fine and well rested. At around 9:30am I was at a flower nursery when I began to feel extremely nauseous, anxious, and started having lightheaded/dizzy spells. I proceeded to drive home, an approximately 7 minute drive, where I immediately began to have violent vomiting and diarrhea. While this was occurring I began having muscle cramps with extreme fatigue and shaking. After 20 minutes of this my girlfriend helped me into bed. Once in bed we realized I also had a fever of 103F. While in bed I had a cold washcloth on my forehead to try and bring down my fever. I had cold sweats and chills while in bed. For the next two hours I would periodically go back and forth from the bed to the toilet with both vomiting and diarrhea. I finally fell asleep and woke up at 7:00pm. I no longer felt nauseous, I had a temperature of 99.2F, I felt very cold, and felt extremely fatigued. Knowing I needed fluids and nutrition, I had some chicken noodle soup with water and Pedialyte. After eating the soup, my stomach felt fine so I ate some more with bread. We went to bed around 10:00pm. I had zero nausea, no fever, but still felt very weak and exhausted. I woke up at approximately 2:30am with a diarrhea accident in bed. I immediately ran to the bathroom where I continued having diarrhea, dry heaving, stomach cramping, and shaking while my girlfriend started the laundry and put on new bedding. After 30-40 minutes being at the toilet I went back to bed where I had a fever of 101.6F. I placed a cold washcloth on my forehead and eventually fell asleep. I did also recognize a rise in my heart rate when I would go to bed. For the next two days I laid in bed trying to rest while periodically trying to eat and drink fluids. However, I continued to vomit and have diarrhea throughout both days with fatigue and body aches. I also began to recognize a rise in my heartrate when I laid in bed. I began to feel my heart beating from my chest and in my temples. By 3/29/2021 I no longer had periodic fevers, regular nausea, or body aches but I did begin to recognize food sensitivities. For the next 10 days, I did not have a single solid stool and slowly identified foods that made me nauseous. I found my 100% Premium Grass-fed whey protein? shakes were causing nausea within 5 minutes of drinking. Before the vaccine, I never had any stomach issues drinking these protein shakes. I used this brand and this specific protein powder for 2 years on a regular daily basis. I also identified spicy foods were now causing cramping, bloating, and nausea. Which before the vaccine, I also never had a stomach related issue with at all and had a high tolerance for spicy foods. I finally found myself becoming nauseated after eating yogurt. Before the vaccine, every morning I would make parfaits with 100% grass-fed Greek yogurt, organic granola, and organic blackberries. By 4/8/2021, after recognizing foods sensitivities and adjusting my diet, I finally began to have solid stools. I have received a significant amount of vaccines due to my time in the military. This was the first time in my entire life I had ever experienced an any type of adverse reaction to a vaccine. *As a note: I also received adverse effects to my second dose of the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine*

SYMPTOM_TEXT: (I received both Pfizer vaccines, but there was only room to report one. I received the first vaccine on 5/12/21 and felt sick for a few days. The details here will be about what happened after the second dose which I received on 6/2/21). The evening after getting the second dose of the Pfizer Covid 19 vaccine, I began to feel body aches and had a low fever. That persisted on and off for four days. The fatigue from that didn't seem to get better. As time went over over the next few weeks. I was sleeping a lot, with extreme muscle weakness. I normally exercise frequently and am a healthy adult, but it was extremely difficult to catch my breath when running, and I had trouble breathing when I was singing ( I could only sing a couple words before having to gasp for breath again). I made an appointment with my doc and she ordered blood tests. Before I could get those results, my health had declined to the point where I was taking several naps throughout the day, my muscles felt extremely weak, and joint pain (which I had never had before) was getting extreme. It was so bad I could barely walk in the morning, and my normal tennis days were impossible. I also had a bizarre stabbing pain in the top of my right foot. I began to wonder if I would be able to go back to work in the Fall (I'm a teacher). This was crazy! I'm a healthy adult woman with no health problems! I thought my life was over as I knew it. The results from my blood tests showed that I had possible lupus. I had full blood work done as part of a physical just before my vaccines and everything was normal. Out of desperation, I began a severe elimination diet to try to cut down on inflammation. (I've been a distance runner most of my adult life and was super scared my joints were getting damaged). Within a day of starting that diet (basically eating just meat), my joint pain went away. Later that month, one of the three lupus markers my doctor had tested for came back normal (the other two were still positive for possible lupus). The fatigue continued and is still present. I must take a nap daily, and leave work feeling like I can barely stay awake. I am still eating my super strict diet and as soon as I stray from it a little bit, the joint pain returns with a vengeance. I don't know how I'm going to return to a normal life. I have a rheumatolist appointment scheduled for January.
OTHER_MEDS: No meds. Multi-vitamin, vitamin D, zinc, magnesium

Patient is a 32 y.o. male with no significant medical history who was admitted from the ED for chest pain.  Patient has minimal medical comorbidities.      Patient reported substernal chest pain that has awoke him from sleep. He reported that he had a viral type symptoms earlier this week including a sore throat, body aches, an intermittent headaches that lasted for a couple a days.  During this time he had a strep test on 10/28/2021 which was negative.  These symptom resolved.  Patient had his 1st COVID-19 vaccination (Pfiszer) on 10/19/2021.    In the ED, initial VS included:  Blood pressure 119/70, heart rate 68, respiratory rate 17, oxygen saturation 99% room air, and temperature 36.7 C.  The initial 12 lead ECG showed:  Sinus rhythm at 86 bpm with ST elevation consistent with early repolarization particularly predominant in his inferior and lateral leads.  Laboratory tests were notable for:  Hemoglobin 15.0, hematocrit 44.4, leukocytes 6.4, platelets 268, sodium 138, potassium 5.4, BUN 13, creatinine 0.81, glucose 91, and initial high sensitivity troponin markedly elevated at 574.  2 hour troponin increased to 707.  6 hour troponin was 841 and was trended daily.  Subsequent troponins were 661, 430. CRP was slightly elevated, down trended prior to discharge.  Sed rate was elevated at 27 at the time of admission. Daily EKG were obtained, ST elevation resolved.   Cardiac MRI was obtained on 11/01/2021.  MR findings are consistent with acute myocarditis with myocardial edema and corresponding scattered foci of sub pericardial delayed enhancement in the LV.  LV is of normal size with preserved systolic function, calculated LVEF 53%.  RV is normal size and systolic function, no delayed enhancement seen in the RV free or inferior walls.   Consultation to discuss vaccine recommendations in this setting.  At this time it is recommended that he not receive mRNA vaccinations.   His history, presentation, physical and diagnostic findings consistent with myocarditis were discussed with MD. He recommends no specific day-to-day restrictions.  Patient was advised to avoid competitive sports for 3 months and to follow up with a cardiac MRI in 3 months as well as a follow-up in a clinic. If symptoms of recurrent chest discomfort or dyspnea, he should be seen sooner.

Around 11:30am I began to notice my shoulder being sore at the shot injection site. This was a symptom I did not experience during my first dose of the vaccine. Around 3:00pm I began to feel extremely fatigued. Around 7:00pm my head began to feel congested, I had trouble staying warm, and I began to start a fever. After lying in bed I began to have chills, body aches, and shaking with a fever of 101.4F. I also developed a light cough. I stayed home and laid in bed for the next two days with periodic chills, periodic fevers, and extreme fatigue. The second night (4/13/2021) I began to have uncontrollable coughing fits to the point of dry-heaving, but had no vomiting. From 4/15/2021 until 4/25/2021 I continued to have a deep lingering cough. But no other symptoms.
