(influenza and COVID booster dose)  Hospital Emergency;  11/20/2021 CHIEF COMPLAINT: POSSIBLE ALLERGIC REACTION (Had Flu shot and Pfizer booster shot today, now having swelling to upper lip worsening. Took tylenol at 2215. Was having neck pain and chills - resolved with tylenol. ) DIAGNOSIS at time of disposition: 1. Angioedema, initial encounter  Follow-up Information  Call, MD.  Specialty: Family Medicine  ED Course as of 11/21/21 0151 Sun Nov 21, 2021 0137 Patient is a very pleasant 19-year-old female that presents emergency department with swelling to her upper lip that she noticed about 40 minutes prior to arrival.  She states she received her Pfizer booster and her influenza vaccine around 11:00 a.m., just after 10:00 p.m. she began developed some subjective fevers chills and body ache and neck ache and noticed swelling to her upper lip.  The Tylenol resolved all the symptoms except her lip and thus she presented to the emergency department for evaluation.  She denies any tongue swelling, no feeling her throat closing, no difficulty swallowing or breathing.  On exam she had mild upper lip swelling but thankfully the rest of her exam was reassuring.  She states her lips felt pruritic but she had no evidence of urticaria on exam.  An IV was started, the patient was provided Solu-Medrol, Pepcid, Benadryl and monitored closely for the last nearly 3 hours duration.  The patient was checked several times, the most recent of which showed improvement of her lip swelling (although not full resolution). Thankfully she is well-appearing and not showing evidence of anaphylaxis.  She has had no new symptoms or worsening symptoms.  Plan is for the patient to be able to go at the 3 hour mark.  I have written her for Prednisone for home for the next 5 days, and discussed use of OTC Benadryl and Pepcid for the next 5 days.  I have advised her that she should likely not receive any additional Pfizer COVID vaccine or the standard flu vaccine in the future.  We also discussed emergency department return precautions including a worsening of her lip swelling, swelling to her tongue, the feeling of swelling to her throat, difficulty breathing, or difficulty swallowing.  The patient verbalized understanding instructions all questions were answered.  She and her mother were agreeable with the plan of care discharged home. [EC] 0150 Patient has been in the emergency department for 3 hours, continues to be doing well and to be discharged as previously discussed. [EC]
OTHER_MEDS: Etonogestrel (NEXPLANON SUBCUT) nystatin (MYCOSTATIN) powder predniSONE (DELTASONE) 50 MG tablet

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Arm was sore at the injection site, but around bed time (~10pm) it became so sore I described it as feeling as though I was stabbed in the arm with a knife, or hit with a bullet it was so painful. Around the same time, my body temperature became so cold I had to layer clothes. Normally I sleep in shorts and a t-shirt, but I put on sweat pants, a sweat shirt and socks, sleeping under two blankets, and I was still shivering. The next day this coldness continued, and I added another layer on top and a knit hat. I felt tired apart from the poor sleep, and a little nauseous at times. My appetite was reduced. I finally took my temperature in the afternoon on Nov 23 and it was 99.8. This elevated temperature continued until Nov 24 when I returned to normal.

I had the vaccine at 5PM on the 17th and went home, made dinner, and relaxed when I noticed stiffness in my arm which is pretty normal around 7/8 PM. I then began to feel tired and went to bed at 9:30 PM and woke up at 3 AM 11/18 with excruciating under arm pain and full body pain that was unlike anything I've ever experienced. I have had the flu viruses in the past with body aches and it was nothing like that. I got up and took Aleve to try and alleviate the pain, and that's when I noticed I had severe swelling on underside of my arm on the opposite side of where I had been injected with the vaccine, and I had swelling up into armpit and around the side of my chest and into my breast and up into my collar bone around my neck to the point you couldn't see my collar bone through the skin anymore. It still is somewhat puffy, and we are a week into having the vaccine. I then proceeded to get ready for work and try to go to work because I could with 2nd dose, but by the time I got to work the Aleve had worn off around 8:30 AM and my body just hurt so bad that I had to go home. I called my doctor and asked if I needed to come in but because we're overflowed with COVID-19 patients right now I was told to go home and rest and that is what I did. The body aches didn't pass until morning on the 19th. The best way that I could describe the body pain that I felt was that if needles pushed into my joints all the way back up my neck, back, fingers, toes, and had them be pulled out and pushed back in and set on fire. It was even in my jaw, and I could feel all my teeth and the swelling in my underarm especially in my armpit felt like a water balloon in it because there was so much fluid built up from the swelling. My chest was bruised from the swelling. It's finally starting to go down and I'm able to see my collar bone through my skin again. The fever and everything else were pretty typical with the first two. The 2 days in recovery on the 19th and 20th, I was experienced muscle spasms following the body pain, specifically in my back and abdomen. Today is the best I've felt since last Wednesday.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my second dose of the pfizer covid vaccine on 14Oct2021 at 18weeks pregnant. This is my first pregnancy and up until my adverse event it had been textbook. I have no significant medical history either personally or family.  On November 1st I started to develop left hip pain that gradually got worse with weight bearing and movement. I spoke with my PCM about this as I was concerned with flying on November 8th. After speaking with my PCM and agreeing it was more than likely a muscle strain I just scratched and used heat to try and lessen the pain. I looked up DVT symptoms and pregnancy recommendations while flying and with the good to go from my doctor i went on my 4 hour flight being sure to get up and walk every hour. By November 9th my left leg had started to swell and on the 10th I went to the ER. I was admitted to a local hospital and was diagnosed with a blood clot that extended from my external iliac vein to my popliteal segment of femoral vein I was put on blood thinners and was taken by ambulance from that hospital to another HCF. I was there for roughly 24 hour on blood thinners and was discharged with a status of high risk and am on blood thinners for at least 6 weeks after my delivery.
LAB_DATA: I had lots of blood work down while admitted to the hospital.

Hospitalized (11.18.21);  COVID-19 positive (11.18.21);  Fully Vaccinated  Admission Date: 11/18/2021 Discharge Date: Nov 23, 2021 DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: PRESENTING PROBLEM: Pneumonia due to COVID-19 virus [U07.1, J12.82] HOSPITAL COURSE:PT is a 65 year old female with a past medical history of type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and hyperlipidemia who had received a COVID vaccine who presented with 2 weeks of symptoms including body aches, anorexia, nausea, and diarrhea.  She was found to be Covid-19 positive with hypoxia in the emergency department and was started on supplemental oxygen and dexamethasone.  At time of admission, she was found to have mildly elevated procalcitonin with findings of lobar consolidation on chest x-ray consistent with a community-acquired pneumonia.  After presenting with several days of diarrhea and poor appetite, she was noted to have an AKI with hypovolemic hyponatremia in the setting of dehydration and was treated with IV fluids.  Her blood sugars were noted to be very labile while on steroids, her home Lantus dose was increased and she received corrective insulin while inpatient.  She required up to 6L oxygen by NC and was weaned to room air prior to discharge. She was treated with ceftriaxone and azithromycin for a total course of 5 days.  She did not qualify for remdesivir, but was treated with steroids, started on dexamethasone in hospital and discharged with instructions continue dexamethasone course as outpatient. Patient was discharged in stable condition, in no acute distress, afebrile, with O2Sat >92% on room air.   Pulmrehab evaluated the patient with ambulating desat to 88% but patient declined home oxygen. Patient will continue dexamethasone at discharge to complete 10 total days. Patient seen by regulatory authortity with home insulin and DM medication reccs at discharge as noted.

Hospital course: Patient is a 63 y.o. female with a past medical history significant for non-small cell lung cancer with multiple brain mets who has been on treatment with Entrectinib and completed SRS radiation to her brain. She has mild ataxia at baseline. She presented to ER from home per EMS after she was found on the floor by her family and helped back to bed. She was hypoxic in the 80's when checked by EMS and placed on 4L/NC. She was diagnosed with COVID 11/5 when she was tested due to her husband and son testing positive. Pt's CXR and CTA thorax both demonstrated patchy ground glass infiltrates consistent with COVID pneumonia. The patient was admitted for further evaluation and management. She was started on dexamethasone 6 mg and Remdesivir. She was also given compassionate use monoclonal antibodies on 11/18. She completed the course of remdesivir and 5 days of steroids. Her SOB resolved and she was weaned to RA. Her only remaining symptom at time of discharge was a cough. The patient was eating and ambulating at the time of discharge. Discharge medications and follow up as listed below. Answered all questions and the patient was comfortable with the discharge plan.

Started with sore arm in early afternoon, as expected and as experienced with the first and second doses of the vaccine.  By early evening I started experiencing moderate aches in my ankle joints and it was very painful to walk.  By the time I went to bed @ 9:30 pm the pain had progressed to many more joints and I began to feel extremely chilled.  At 10:30 pm I turned on my heated mattress pad, which helped the chills, but the pain in my joints kept waking me up repeatedly.  By 1:30 am 11-23-2021 I could not stand the pain any longer and got out of bed to find some pain relief medication, falling once in the attempt.  I took 1 tablet of Naproxen and about 30 minutes later the pain had dimmed enough that I was able to get back to sleep.  The joint pain continued Tuesday, 11-23-2021, and I have continued to take one Naproxen tablet- 225 mg every 8 hours to keep the pain bearable.  As of today, Wednesday, 11-24-2021, the joint pain is still present, but is gradually lessening.
OTHER_MEDS: AM:  Methylphenidate, Citalopram, Januvia, Loratadine, Exetimibe, Metoprolol;  PM:  Montelukast, Esomeprazole, Diphenhydramine, Alprazolam.

By that evening I felt lethargic, had chills with a temp. of 100.5 and a sore arm.  I took one tylenol and one ibuprophen and went to bed. During the night I woke up with generalized aches and severe pain in my lumbar spine.  Again waking up with aches and severe pain in my shoulder joint (not the shot arm).  And again woke up with severe spinal neck pain, generalized achiness and headache.  During the night the  achiness was so severe that I could hardly turn over in bed.  The next morning my temp was 100.8 I took 1 tylenol  and 2 ibuprophen. I was so tired and weak I just sat there in the house.   By the second morning I had recovered from the side effects.  Really, the booster side effects were just like the way I felt when I was sick covid breakthrough infection.   In my entire life I have never had such a reaction or any reaction to any vaccination for any disease ever.

During the night I experienced flu-like symptoms (alternating chills and sweat, muscle pain, nausea and dizziness). I woke feeling nauseated around 3:45 a.m. and went to the bathroom. I was overcome with sweats and dizziness on the way there and took a break to lie down on the floor for a few minutes. Then I got up and made it to the toilet to urinate. While sitting there, darkness crept in on my vision and I experienced ringing in my ears. I knew I was about to faint and called for my husband. By the time he arrived in the bathroom, I was unconscious. He said that I was completely rigid and my eyes had rolled to the side of my head but were open. He called 911, managed to wake me, and drove me to the emergency room. I felt sweaty and dizzy when I woke and my husband said my sentences were not completely coherent.

Was sitting in chair after the vaccine. 2-3 min after given pt fell to the floor from sitting position, mom opened door to alert us. Pt was awake and responsive, mom states that she did not think he passed out as when she knealed down he was looking at her. Pt stood up with help form mom and went and sat in chair again. Not pale, no increased RR. When asking pt how he felt he said good. Asked him if room was spinning and he said no. While asking him these his questions he kept closing his eyes or his eyes were rolling back. Lifted pt up onto exam table and had him lay down. He was responsive but did seem a little more tired. Asked him and he said he was a little sleepy. Asked him if he had felt that way before the vaccine and he said yes. Took BP and was on low side 89/58.  Pt laid down and monitored in office for 40 min. Recheck BP 30 min after was- 97/62. Pt was fully responsive although quiet, said he was still sleepy. Informed mom for next vaccine he will need to lay down while getting it and remain laying down the whole 30 min.

After administering the vaccine to the customer, he was advised to wait 15-20 minutes in the waiting area, which he did. I returned to the pharmacy and after a few minutes, another customer in the waiting area said the source individual was having a bad reaction. I immediately rushed over and say the patient reclined more than normal in his chair. There was a rack holding canes behind his chair which he had knocked over, presumably with his head. I approached the patient and his eyes were rolling all over (back and forth, left and right) for approximately ten seconds, during which time he was totally unaware of his surroundings. After approximately ten seconds, he mentally returned "to normal", for the first time noticed that I was standing there and asked "what happened?" I explained to him he was having an adverse reaction to the COVID shot. He said he felt lightheaded and extremely warm, so I advised him that we should take his sweatshirt off, which he did. We also gave him an ice pack to place on his forehead and a bottle of cold water to drink. He was completely coherent by this point and said he had no other symptoms. 911 was called upon my immediate entrance to the scene by the front end manager. I stayed with the patient until first responders came. Soon after, EMS arrived to evaluate the patient. I returned to the pharmacy at this point. After a few minutes, I returned to the waiting area and the patient along with EMS were gone. It is unknown if the patient received any medical treatment or if he was taken by EMS to the hospital.

I received the Shingles vaccine around 05/21/2021. We went away on 05/27/2021 and on the 28th I was climbing and, all of a sudden, I felt like I was on fire from my knees down, especially my feet. It was located on both legs but more on the left side. The damage initially on my left leg was from the statins. My legs felt frozen but my feet were burning. I pushed myself to keep exercising. I ended up going to physical therapy 2-3 times a week. The physical therapist told me my muscles were abnormally stiff. She had me doing asymmetric exercises with my feet. Today I could finally move my toes again. The pharmacist who gave me the Shingles vaccine said it was alright to receive the vaccine 6 weeks after the COVID-19 vaccine. It ended up giving me what we call fake shingles. I had Neuralgia and Neuropathy. Apparently the COVID-19  vaccine can activate shingles. It could also be traced all the way to 2007 when I had the Statins. The neurologist checked my reflexes. I feel like they do not know what to do. After the booster vaccine I have been very tired. This whole journey has been very emotional. I went to the ER in the end of June, I took too much Magnesium and my ribs felt really tight. I called my PAC and she told me to go to urgent care. I went in and they did some lab work and by that time I was feeling better. Then I got a call saying I needed to go to the ER immediately because my blood clotting factor was high so we jumped in the car and they put me in a wheelchair. They told me I could not eat, drink, or walk because they needed to do some tests. 6 hours and a half later they put me in a room and I heard a doctor outside laughing and they did not come in. At 10:30PM I walked out and I said this was crazy. 10:50PM the doctor came in and he said they were not doing any more tests, the results of my testing were inconsistent with my age. So they said there was nothing wrong with me and they let me go home. It was awful.
OTHER_MEDS: Lialda Calcium Turmeric Magnesium Vitamin C Carnitine
HISTORY: LPR Ulcerative Colitis, I am in total remission from Ulcerative Colitis from Statins I took back in 2007

She reported that her symptoms started on 11/11/21 with cough and cold like symptoms, but then on 11/12/21 she became nauseous and started vomiting.  She had no abdominal pain.  Her glucose that evening was 400 and she continued to treat herself with her insulin pump but was having a difficult time getting her glucose to downtrend.  She added subcutaneous insulin and was finally able to get her glucose down to about 150 on 11/13/21 but since then has not been able to keep any oral intake down.  Upon arrival to the ED she presented with mild hypertension with a SBP in the 160s, otherwise vitals were stable and appropriate.  Her CBC was unremarkable.  Her CMP revealed a K of 2.8 a Cl of 97, Ca of 10.4, glucose of 210, and a BUN/creatinine of 36/1.11, respectively.  Her anion gap was 36.  A d-dimer was 570.  Her serum ketones were 3.0.  Her UDS was positive for cannabinoids.  Her UA was positive for protein at 100, neg for glucose, and 20 ketones, but was not indicative of infection.  She was negative for influenza A/B and RSV, but tested positive for COVID-19.  ABG were drawn and revealed 7.45/33/22. A CXR revealed mild atelectasis in the right base.  In the ED she was given Inapsine, a bolus of IVF, IV famotidine, and IV potassium.  She was admitted to the ICU for further evaluation and management. She was seen in the ICU this morning. Very anxious and emotional.  VSS.  No acute events noted overnight.  Had clears last NOC and did not tolerate well, increased nausea and increased anxiety.  She denies pain but admits to general malaise and body aches.  No other medical complaints this AM.  Hospital Course 1. Diabetic keto acidosis ... 3. Intractable nausea/vomiting 4. COVID-19

Patient was at some point requiring 40 L of oxygen by high flow nasal cannula in the intensive care unit and now is currently on room air saturating between 89 and 92% feeling comfortable.   He is going to go home with 5 more days of dexamethasone to complete a bit more of 10 days. He has 1 refill at hand and has been instructed to take it back immediately if he feels that the symptoms get much worse after he runs out of the medication. She reported that her daughter, the patient, had received the Pfizer booster at this clinic earlier in the day, and she is also under 18 years of age (and not immunocompromised).  I  informed the mother that the RN vaccinator had mistakenly given her daughter the booster, which is only approved for individuals 18 and older. This was a medication administration error.  I consulted with Dr., Deputy Public Health Officer on 11/22/21.  I followed up with mother of patient on 11/22/21 by phone. Mother reported that her daughter did not experience any side effects from the vaccine, and she felt fine.  I informed mother that this 3rd dose for her daughter is considered her booster shot, and that the booster should not be repeated.

Presented to Er on 11/13/21 and was admitted.  This is a 74-year-old female with a prior history of CKD stage IIIB, dilated cardiomyopathy with ejection fraction of 25-30% and post ICD placement, insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus type 2, hypertension, chronic systolic congestive Heart failure who is vaccinated for COVID-19 and presenting with complaints of cough.  She did test positive for COVID.  Workup in the ED did reveal the ABG with the pH that was within normal limits, PO2 of 62.9 pCO2 of 46.6.  Oxygen saturation was 90.7 on room air.  X-ray did reveal no acute cardiopulmonary disease.  CT chest without contrast did reveal mild peribronchial thickening likely suggestive of bronchitis otherwise no focal pneumonia or ground-glass disease.  Initially she was started on Rocephin azithromycin Decadron as she was mildly hypoxic and tachypneic.  She did significantly improve overnight.  Continue to have a cough that was predominantly nonproductive.  She however remained stable on room air.  Therefore was stable for discharge.  O2 walk was performed prior to discharge and now patient did not require any supplemental oxygen.  She was discharged on a course of azithromycin. Discharged on 11/14/21

I had a telehealth visit with my physician, and she diagnosed that I was having an allergic reaction, but we could not pinpoint the cause.  On 1/23/2021, she prescribed a six day course of 10 mg Prednisone, Hydroxyzine HCl 25 mg every four hours, and Triamcinolone Acetonide Ointment USP, 0.1% topical ointment to treat the rash. I hope this information is helpful.

He was able to move out of the ICU on 11/17. He had an ECHO showing EF 58%. His procalcitonin was elevated and he was felt to have secondary bacterial pneumonia and he was started on azithromycin and rocephin.  Over the course of the hospital stay his oxygen needs gradually diminished and by the day of discharge he was down to room air at rest and 3 L with activity.  He completed his antibiotic course of Rocephin and azithromycin during his hospital stay and did not require further antibiotics at discharge.  He was discharged on dexamethasone to complete an additional 5 days.  Additionally given his AFib on admission this thought this was possibly related to his acute infectious process.  Consideration could be given to doing a ZIO patch in the future to assess his amount of AFib when not acutely ill.  His chads Vasc score was 1 has recommended that he take aspirin 81 daily.  His lisinopril was discontinued and he was started on metoprolol 25mg 2 times a day.  If he remains in sinus rhythm he could eventually be converted back to his lisinopril.

I had issues with both shots. First shot, I started with a general headache that eased with time, but it never went away. After the 2nd shot, I had a more localized headache (feeling like pressure) on the back side of my head (left side). In addition, I lost hearing on my right ear suddenly. It started as a feeling of being in a tunnel or underwater. I realized that I could not recognize sound coming from my right ear and I couldn't understand when people talked to me.  I had my 1st Dr's visit on Oct 9th at Health center. I had a follow up appt on Oct 18th and a referral was placed for ENT. I had my appt with on 11/23 with ENT.  In terms of the pressure headache, my Dr said it could be occipital neuralgia, although there has not been trauma to my head or neck. All these events happened after my 2nd shot. I am not sure if they are related to the COVID shots or not, but I would like to report them. I did not feel headaches until the initial headaches with the 1st shot and, after my 2nd one, the headache localized in the back on my head AND the sudden hearing loss. Again, I am not sure if they are related or a coincidence, but I think I should report them.  In terms of 'what's next', ENT suggested transtympanic steroid injections, although he thinks this will not work because it has been over 2 months since I noticed my hearing loss. Also suggested hearing aid.  For the headache, I am now applying heat, although my family doctor suggested gavapentin.  Again, I am not sure if this is due to the COVID shots or not, but I think I should report it since it happened right after my shots.
LAB_DATA: I had an audiology test on Nov 23rd. Results on the right ear were moderate to severe SNHL through 6kHz rising to normal @8kHz-mild SNHL 2-6k-Hz. The speech essentially not understanding with masking on my right ear. No signs of fluid.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: ER note 11/21/2021:  Cough, body aches, congestion and right upper quadrant abdominal pain  -patient is found to be Covid positive.  She is febrile and tachycardic in the emergency department.  She states she has been taking Tylenol with the limited relief.  She was given ibuprofen for her fever and a small fluid bolus. EKG shows sinus tachycardia with no evidence of acute ischemic changes.  Her white blood cell count is minimally elevated at 14.2.  Hemoglobin, hematocrit and platelets are all found to be normal.  Patient is hyperglycemic at 375, however no evidence of DKA.  While her liver enzymes are minimally elevated with an alkaline phosphatase of 179, and AST of 103 and an ALT of 93 with a normal bilirubin patient does have a history of having elevated liver enzymes and had a remote cholecystectomy.  Lactic acid is elevated at 3.4.  Troponin is normal at 8.9.  Ferritin is elevated at 867.8.  Urine does not show any evidence of urinary tract infection.  Upon arrival to the emergency department her pulse ox was in the low 90s.  With ambulation it did stay above 88%.  She was resting in the room awaiting her test results when it did dip to 87%.  It then returned to the low 90s without oxygen administration.  Patient was given dexamethasone for treatment.  Bilateral patchy infiltrates are seen on the x-ray.  Patient's D-dimer is minimally elevated at 594.  Low suspicion for PE at this time.  Discussed with Dr. who is agreeable to admit the patient. At the time of this VAERS entry, the patient is still admitted to the Adult Care Unit.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 11/22/21: Sore arm began that evening at around 8pm but laid down for bed at 9pm. From 10pm-2am, I experienced a fiery burning in every joint in my body for the course of four hours. It was some of the most severe pain I have felt in my life. I can only explain it as a hot poker being jabbed into every joint, even my ribs. I could not move either. At around 2am, the pain almost instantly stopped, and I immediately got cold. My teeth were chattering, and I could not warm up. I did not take my temperature but assume it had to be high. To warm up, I took a half hour shower. When I got out, I had a migraine and started throwing up. By 3am or so, I got into bed, sweating and feeling extremely hot rather than freezing. I woke up again in the morning, feeling rundown. After waking up at 8am, I also slept from 10am-11:30am, 1:30pm-3:00pm, and 4:30pm-10:30pm. I did not have an appetite all day.   Throughout the course of this, I took Tylenol at 650mg dosage, but it only affected the injection site, which I thought was odd. I do not normally swallow pills, so my tolerance is extremely low, and I am usually able to get away with a dose of children's Tylenol, even as a 25 year old.   By 11/24, I am not exhausted, but I still have lingering pain that comes and goes. At the time of writing this at 5pm on 11/24 most of the pain is gone, though some joints still throb if they're bent for too long.

We had an incident of Post Vaccination Syncope at store 4677. I gave an elderly lady her Pfizer Booster shot and asked her to wait in the post vaccination benches. Since   she got the shot at 1:30 pm (the pharmacy closed at lunch) I told the patient I will be keeping an eye on how she is doing even though the doors are closed .  When i went outside to see how the patient is doing her grandson who is a nurse told me that the patient is feeling warm and thirsty. When I looked at the patient she looked very Pale and stiff. She wasn't comprehending very well when I asked her how she is doing. With the help of her grandson, we made the patient lie down on the benches and elevated her feet.   Code white was alerted and I gave patient Cold Compress on her forehead and around the neck area. Shortly after doing cold compress patient started talking and she stated she is feeling better.  We gave her some water and she waited in the pharmacy for about half an hour.  Patient was very happy with the care she got throughout the episode and was very thankful!!

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Back in April, I was meditating, and I started to have heart palpitations. Which was like a fluttering in my chest and being out of breath even though I wasn't moving. It felt like my heart skipped a beat and my heart was racing. It happened from 7PM-4AM every few minutes. I've had these feelings before where it would happen once or twice. But because this happened over and over again for many hours, that's why I contacted my doctor. These palpitations were happening for several hours for 2-3 minutes. I remember it kept me from being able to go to sleep. For the next week, I had them intermittently so it didn't happen often, but it would happen a few times a day for a few weeks. I was told to cut out the protein supplements by my doctor. But the palpitations wouldn't go away and eventually went away after a month. I still have them occasionally, but not as frequent and intense. For treatment, I went in for a EKG and that came back normal. They had me wear a heart monitor for 2 weeks and sent it in. The heart monitor helped with diagnosis of atrial fibrillation, but the monitor showed that it was less than 1% of the time. Taking a low dose aspirin daily to prevent stroke and blood clots.
LAB_DATA: EKG Normal Heart Monitor 2 weeks showed atrial fibrillation for less than 1% of the time Heart Ultrasound Normal

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Per report by RN who vaccinated patient:  Pt received 1st Covid vaccine, and after the vaccination was standing by her mother watching her sister get vaccinated.  Suddenly she fainted, slumped to floor; she did not hit her head. She lost consciousness for less than 10 seconds. Her father picked her up and put her on his lap.  1st Aid RN and EMT on site responded. Applied ice pack to back of her neck. Pt was pale, diaphoretic and oriented x3. At this time, the father revealed that child has history of fainting with shots (which parents did not inform clinical staff of prior to vaccination). Dad carried child to 1st aid station where she was assessed and monitored. She was placed supine on cot with feet elevated; pallid and slow to verbal response. 10:35 vital signs B/P 102/68, pulse 81 bpm, O2 99%.  Pt slowly regained color, had water and crackers. Vital signs sitting up B/P 98/68, O2 98%. Pt still slow to respond and lethargic. Paramedics called at 11:00, arrived at 11:10. Assessed child and interviewed parents, made decision to not transport. Pt became more animated, color returned and able to stand and walk safely on her own. 11:20 Family left clinic.

Upon pumping the cuff, patient passed out with seizure like activity, after about 10 seconds he came to. patient complained of being hot and sweaty.  No complaints of trouble breathing or itchiness. At 2:00pm vitals were 152/80 BP, 97 O2, 59 HR.  EMS arrived on scene. At 2:09pm EMS had patient try to stand. At 2:12pm patient was complaining of lightheadedness and being sweaty. My husband was talking to a patient  on 11/24/21 about the vaccine and she told my husband her friend and her friend's husband are having the same issue, except her friend's husband is deaf in both ears.  When they spoke to someone, not sure if it was their doctor, Pfizer or someone else, they were told not to say anything because it's a well known side effect and they don't want people to know about it because they don't want people dissuaded from getting the vaccine.  I was told my hearing may not come back.  Needless to say, I am very angry about it as I am a lawyer, I work in Medicine, and I also fly planes.  This will ground me from ever flying a plane again and it interferes substantially with my daily living activities and work.

I was also constantly leaving my purse of phone at stores after this time. In mid June, I discovered that my thyroid medication needed to be adjusted and my confusion and inability to find my way around seemed to fix itself very shortly after a medication adjustment. However, I just received my booster shot on Nov 4, 2021, and my cognitive issues are increasing again (having difficulty figuring out how to get from point A to B in my community, forgetting things, easily confused). I was sleeping in a wet bed. In the morning, Nurse Aid assisted me in replacing the wet bed. I couldn't move, and  I was still very dizzy with a headache. On 28OCT2021, I was staying in bed because I couldn't move all day long. On 29OCT2021, My physical conditions worsened, BP: 178/120 mmHg, HR: 136/min- 54/min, I had difficulty breathing, SPO2 94%, and I devolved bowel movement incontinence and urinary retention. Admission Date: November 17, 2021 Discharge Date: November 22, 2021 Pneumonia due to COVID-19 virus HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: PT is a 92 y.o. male PMHx of PVD, HTN, BPH, GERD who presents today with weakness and cough. He states 5 days PTA he developed weakness. He lives at home with a friend and is independent with ADLs but states he's been needing to use a cane to ambulate due to weakness. Two days PTA he developed productive cough, SOB as well as decreased appetite. He drank 2 12 oz glasses of water this morning and doesn't think he drinks enough water. He denies any myalgia but endorsed an episode of flank pain. Due to his progressive symptoms he came to the ED. In the ED he was afebrile, normal HR and RR but hypertensive and SpO2 down to 90 percent on room air. He was placed on 2L NC.  Labs significant for Hb 11.0, normal WBC, Na 123, BUN 24, creatinine 1.01, troponin 37 and 38 on repeat. UA with proteniuria but otherwise bland. EKG with NSR. CXR with bilateral infiltrates. He was given dexamethasone, calcium gluconate, tylenol and zofran and admitted for further evaluation. Assessment and Plan COVID-19 PNA Acute hypoxic respiratory insufficiency secondary to above - pt with SOB, cough, chest x-ray with bilateral infiltrates - pt vaccinated in 3/2021, due for booster - continue dexamethasone 6 mg daily x 10 days - continuous pulse ox - the patient is on 2L NC - Lovenox for VTE prophylaxis - supportive care REHAB admission:  Admission Date: 11/22/2021 Discharge Date: 11/24/21 11/24: unfortunately, the patient had increasing O2 requirements the AM of 11/24 ultimately requiring 12L on Venturi mask to maintain saturations in 90s. Hospitalist consult placed. Venous doppler bilateral lower extremities unremarkable for DVT, but given concern for clinical deterioration, decision was made to discharge patient from rehab and admit to acute care hospital. COVID-19 pneumonia Acute hypoxic respiratory failure 2/2 COVID 11/23: continue supplemental O2 PRN to maintain in 90s. CXR with bilateral infiltrates, Pt was vaccinated 3/2021. Had not received booster. Was not given remdesivir or monoclonal antibodies, is on steroids - dexamethasone 6 mg daily for 10d, started 11/18. + test 11/17. HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: Patient is a 92 y.o. male with a past medical history of GERD, BPH, PVD and hypertension who presented to Hospital on 11/17 with weakness and cough that started five days prior.  He found to be COVID-19 positive.  He had both vaccines (Pfizer - last dose 3/3021) but had not had the booster shot. He was found to be hyponatremic and hypoxic - requiring 2 L O2 NC.  He was started on Decadron 6 mg.  Nephrology was consulted to manage his hyponatremia.  Nephrology felt the symptoms were consistent with SIADH and the patient was started on a fluid restriction.  Ultimately he was also started on sodium tablets with improvement of his hyponatremia.  The patient was able to be weaned to room air at times and other times did require 1-2 L O2,  He was felt stable for discharge to rehab on 11/23.  After discharge the patient's oxygen requirements have been increasing.  The patient has a persistent non-productive cough.  He denies any further increase in dyspnea or work of breathing.  He does note some calf discomfort, more on the right side.  No LE edema.  Denies chest pain.  Was having some "ribs" pain with coughing - now his coughing hurts in his hip.  On review the patient has been mildly hypertensive since admission.  No fevers.  He does report feeling more overall weak and fatigued. Given the patient's respiratory status, he is no longer appropriate for rehab, he will be transferred to inpatient.

ED 11.20.21; hospitalized 11.21.21; COVID-19 positive (11.20.21);  fully vaccinated Admitted for hypotension, septic shock, COVID-19 (with ESRD, cardiomyopathy, bilateral PE) Admission Date: 11/21/2021 Date of Death: 11/23/21 Time of Death: 12:59 PM Preliminary Cause of Death: Hypotension DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: PRESENTING PROBLEM: Shock (HCC) [R57.9] Hypotension [I95.9] HOSPITAL COURSE: This is a 77 year old male with a PMH significant for HTN, HLD, ESRD on HD, T2DM with retinopathy & neuropathy, gout, hemochromatosis, hyperparathyroidism, cardiomyopathy, OSA on BiPAP, CAD and obesity who was brought to the emergency department on 11/20 by EMS from his care facility with concerns of hypotension. The patient was noted to be hypotensive on initial evaluation and was given Levophed, also found to be positive for COVID-19 and noted to have CT thorax findings of large right effusion unchanged from prior imaging, increasing moderate left effusion, as well as patchy airspace disease in the right upper lobe and right middle lob suggestive of pneumonia representative of changes secondary to COVID-19 with inflammatory changes and early bacterial pneumonia. There was also question about the possibility of a PE on the CT thorax, however it was deemed unlikely as the patient had been anticoagulated with Warfarin for Atrial Fibrillation with therapeutic INR. The patient was started on broad spectrum antibiotics for bacterial pneumonia and was started on Remdesivir and Decadron for treatment of COVID-19 with admission for further evaluation and management. On the first full day after his ER visit that led to admission, the patient had elected not to pursue treatments any further. Hospice was consulted and patient/patient's family ultimately elected for inpatient hospice. Nephrology had been consulted for assistance with the patient's dialysis, although they ultimately signed off the patient's care due to patient choosing not to pursue further treatment and deciding to pursue inpatient hospice care. During the patient's hospitalization, his ICD was turned off given the patient's decision for hospice care. The patient was kept comfortable with the help of hospice during the remainder of his hospitalization and he expired comfortably on 11/23/21 with his wife and son at bedside. The patient was pronounced expired at 12:59PM on 11/23/21.

herpes zoster; post herpetic neuralgia; Information has been received from a lawyer referring to a patient of unknown age and gender, regarding a case in litigation. Information about concurrent condition, history condition and concomitant medication was not reported. On an unknown date, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (strength, dose, route, lot# and expiration date unknown) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). After receiving the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient suffered herpes zoster and postherpetic neuralgia. As a result of these symptoms, the patient was seen and treated by medical providers and was still under their care. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of the patient's condition.As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of wrongful conduct, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. The patient also had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of herpes zoster and postherpetic neuralgia was considered as not recovered and causal relationship was assessed as related.  Both events herpes zoster and postherpetic neuralgia were considered as disability by the lawyer.

she is a little bit handicapped; after received the vaccine (PNEUMOVAX), she had soreness in her arm; after she received the FLU shot, she had soreness in her arm; still hurts if she bumps it; This spontaneous report was received from an 86-year-old female patient reporting on herself. The patient's current conditions included glaucoma. The patient had not known drug reactions/allergies.  The patient's medical history included 3 surgeries, physiotherapy, shingles, chickenpox, fall and hip fracture.  Concomitant therapies included atorvastatin, lisinopril, amlodipine besilate and eye drops for glaucoma.  On an unknown date, reported as "few years ago", the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23), one dose, intramuscularly, for pneumonia immunization (dose, site of administration, lot number and expiration date were not reported).   After she received the vaccine, she had soreness in her arm (pain in extremity).  She did not contact her healthcare provider because the soreness was not bad enough and she did not take any medication for treatment of her symptoms.    On 09-NOV-2021, the patient received her annual influenza vaccine (FLU), shot and she had soreness in her arm after vaccination (pain in extremity).  The soreness was better but still hurt if she "bump it" (pain).  The patient stated she recently received her covid-19 vaccine(COVID-19 VACCINE) booster shot.  Also she had received the mumps vaccine (MUMPS VACCINE), diphtheria vaccine (DIPHTHERIA VACCINE), the zoster vaccine live and the shingles vaccine (manufacturer unknown).  The patient stated she was "a little bit handicapped" (disability).  The outcome of disability and pain in extremity was unknown.    The reporter did not assess the causal relationship between suspect therapies with and the events.  Upon internal review disability was determined medically significant.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Chickenpox; Fall; Hip fracture; Physiotherapy; Shingles; Surgery

felt was coming down with a cold; flu like symptoms; whoozy; heart started to race; extremely tired; difficulty sleeping; malaise; increased aches and pains; kidney function is down; bruise when she injected; felt hung over; depressive state; felt foggy; This case was reported by a consumer via other manufacturer and described the occurrence of renal impairment in a 62-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season) for prophylaxis and abaloparatide (Tymlos) for senile osteoporosis.   Concurrent medical conditions included senile osteoporosis. Concomitant products included quetiapine.   On an unknown date, the patient received Shingrix and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season. On 10th August 2021, the patient started Tymlos (subcutaneous) 80 ug once daily (80 ug daily). On 24th August 2021, unknown after receiving Shingrix and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season, the patient experienced renal impairment (serious criteria GSK medically significant), injection site bruising, hangover, depression, foggy feeling in head, fatigue, difficulty sleeping, malaise and pain. On 19th September 2021, the patient experienced wooziness and heartbeats increased. In October 2021, the patient experienced nasopharyngitis and influenza-like symptoms. Tymlos was continued with no change. On an unknown date, the outcome of the renal impairment, injection site bruising, hangover, depression, foggy feeling in head, nasopharyngitis, influenza-like symptoms, fatigue, difficulty sleeping, malaise and pain were unknown and the outcome of the wooziness and heartbeats increased were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the renal impairment, injection site bruising, hangover, depression, foggy feeling in head, nasopharyngitis, influenza-like symptoms, wooziness, fatigue, difficulty sleeping, malaise, pain and heartbeats increased to be related to Shingrix and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season.  Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient experienced dizziness, heart rate increased, fatigue (extreme intensity), renal impairment, injection site bruising, hangover (in the morning), depression, insomnia, feeling abnormal (felt foggy during the day), malaise, pain (increased), nasopharyngitis and influenza like illness. The patient did not take Tymlos and quetiapine for 2 days at bedtime. The patient noted she had taken quetiapine for 2 months prior to Tymlos and felt more energy and was more motivated the 2 days off Tymlos. After the patient had the Shingrix Vaccine (zoster vaccine recombinant, adjuvant) and Influenza vaccinations she held her Tymlos doses from 5th October 2021 to 8th October 2021 or three to seven days due to experiencing flu like symptoms. She felt better while not taking Tymlos. The patient laid down and events of dizziness and heart rate increased resolved.  No treatment was reported. No relevant lab or diagnostic tests were reported. The action taken with Tymlos treatment was dose not changed.  It was unknown if the reporter considered the renal impairment, hangover, depression, foggy feeling in head, nasopharyngitis, influenza-like symptoms, wooziness, heartbeats increased, fatigue, injection site bruising, difficulty sleeping, malaise and pain to be related to Tymlos.

sick (malaise); fever; weakness; chills; Shingles/pain from Shingles rash on back/spots on back/skin crawling/itching/dry heaves; This spontaneous report was received from a 63-year-old female patient via Glaxosmithkline GlaxoSmithKline, reporting on herself. Medical history included that she was diagnosed with shingles 13 years ago. Information regarding concurrent conditions and concomitant medication was not provided.  In approximately 2008, when the rash went away, she received zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for prophylaxis (dosage information, route, lot number and expiration date not reported). On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with varicella zoster vaccine rge (cho) (SHINGRIX) 0.5 (unk) (dosage information, route, lot number and expiration date not reported).      The patient referred that on an unknown date, when she had her first dose of varicella zoster vaccine rge (cho) (SHINGRIX), she was sick (malaise), fever and chills and couldn't get out of bed (weakness) and it lasted 2 days. These events resolved on an unknown date.   On 20-SEP-2021, she received the second dose of varicella zoster vaccine rge (cho) (SHINGRIX). Starting hours after the second dose, she had fever, chills, and she had been sicked all week, nausea, dry heaves and on Tuesday night when she took off the bra, on her back below the neck there was the first spot, kind of dime size. She went back to primary care on Wednesday (22-SEP-2021), started itching, the whole body, felt like her skin was crawling, and the spot on her back had turned into a rash. She was told to take some diphenhydramine (BENADRYL) and put cortisone cream on it, diphenhydramine (BENADRYL) did not help, cortisone cream made it worse, Wednesday was horrible, Thursday the rash was worse, she went back to the doctor and was diagnosed with shingles. The doctor told her to take pregabalin (LYRICA) for the pain from the shingles rash, but she did not take it. Fever, chills, nausea, and dry heaves are resolved. Itching, shingles rash, shingles rash pain, and skin crawling were not resolved. The outcome of shingles was unknown. The patient would like for it to be recorded that she is furious that varicella zoster vaccine rge (cho) (SHINGRIX) caused her shingles outbreak. The causality assessment between zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) and the events was not provided.

Patient had severe throat pain and difficulty in swallowing, lasted for 3 weeks then it went off for few hours and again came back on the right side. Surgeon wanted to do another biopsy but medications started to work after a day. Additionally, inappropriate schedule of vaccine administered was captured. The onset of the event Pemphigus occurred approximately 4 days after the second dose of mRNA- 1273 vaccine. Clinical manifestations included mouth ulceration, lip ulceration, tongue ulceration, odynophagia and dysphagia. Biopsy confirmed the diagnosis of Pemphigus vulgaris. Treatment with topical corticoids was prescribed. Gingival bleeding and Mouth bleeding were also reported, and could be in connection with oral ulcerations. On the other hand, rectal haemorrhage occurred at an unknown date after the second dose. Colonoscopy was performed  approximately 1 month and 6 days after vaccination and haemorrhoids were diagnosed. The rechallenge is not applicable, since the events were reported exclusively after the second dose. The benefit-risk relationship of mRNA- 1273 vaccine is not affected by this report. Rectal haemorrhage was automatically upgraded as serious as per IME list. However, based on information available and due to the lack of evidence of seriousness from a regulatory or clinical standpoint, it was assessed as non-serious.

Concomitant medications included ascorbic acid, chromium, copper, folic acid, inositol, magnesium, manganese, nicotinamide, pantothenic acid, potassium, pyridoxine hydrochloride, retinol, riboflavin, selenium, vitamin b1 nos, vitamin b12 nos, vitamin e nos, zinc (MULTI VIT) taken for an unspecified indication from an unspecified start date and ongoing; fish oil (FISH OIL) taken for an unspecified indication from an unspecified start date and ongoing; amiodarone (AMIODARONE) taken for atrial fibrillation from an unspecified start date and ongoing; amlodipine (AMLODIPINE) taken for atrial fibrillation from an unspecified start date and ongoing; acetylsalicylic acid (ASPIRIN 81) taken for atrial fibrillation from an unspecified start date and ongoing; clonidine (CLONIDINE) taken for hypertension from an unspecified start date and ongoing; fenofibrate (FENOFIBRATE) taken for blood cholesterol from an unspecified start date and ongoing; furosemide (FUROSEMIDE) taken for atrial fibrillation from an unspecified start date and ongoing; lisinopril (LISINOPRIL) taken for hypertension from an unspecified start date and ongoing; atorvastatin calcium (LIPITOR) taken for blood cholesterol from an unspecified start date and ongoing; potassium chloride (POTASSIUM CHLORIDE) taken for hypokalaemia from an unspecified start date and ongoing; warfarin (WARFARIN) taken for atrial fibrillation, cerebrovascular accident from an unspecified start date and ongoing; and insulin human, insulin human injection, isophane (NOVOLIN 30/70) taken for diabetes mellitus, start and stop date were not reported. The patient previously received BNT162B2 (Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 mRNA vaccine) (lot number: EP6955), dose 1, intramuscular, administered in the left deltoid on 29Mar2021 at 15:08 as DOSE 1, SINGLE for COVID-19 immunization with no reported adverse effects. On 28Apr2021, the day following the patient's second dose, she noticed that her left foot was flaccid, dragging and unable to lift it. In two days it continued and progressed to her left knee. In two days it continued and progressed to her right foot, in two days to her right knee and continued to her right hip. At this point , she was unable to walk and could only manage a sliding gait and required use of a cane. The patient also became incontinent on an unspecified date, because she could no longer get to the restroom in her normal timely manner. The patient made an appointment with her primary physician, who thought she had some type of aging disease and referred her to a neurologist. The neurologist ordered a CT scan and an MRI of her brain. Occupational & Physical therapies were prescribed and the patient was referred for a second opinion to specialist because of "gradient susceptibility" and a need to determine whether the patient needed to stop her prescribed baby aspirin and coumadin. The Neurologist instructed her to continue those medications but commented that the patient walked like a drunk. Both neurologists could not determine a cause for her sudden onset ambulation issues. Despite her stroke which resulted in loss of 25% of my abilities, the Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine resulted in an additional loss of 40% of her capabilities. Her gait was now unsteady and she must use an assistive device (cane) that she never needed after her stroke. The adverse event created a financial, physical and emotional hardship for her. To have survived a stroke with a great outcome, but only to have the Pfizer covid-19 vaccine leave her more impaired is a difficult situation to be dealt. The paranasal sinuses are clear; magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) head (11Aug2007): there is no evidence of diffusion restriction. Numerous foci of white matter T2 hyperintensity most consistent with chronic microangiopathic ischemic changes. Focal encephalomalacia and gliotic process noted in the left parietal lobe suggestive for chronic infarct. Small chronic right pontine infarct noted. There is no abnormal postcontrast enhancement intracranially. No evidence of intracranial hemorrhage, mass effect, edema, midline shift, hydrocephalus or extra-axial fluid collection.  Multiple small foci of central and peripheral gradient susceptibility identified. Possible etiologies include hypertension and cerebral amyloid angiopathy; and MRI head (10Jun2021): There is no evidence of diffusion restriction. Numerous foci of white matter T2 hyperintensity most consistent with chronic microangiopathic ischemic changes. Focal encephalomalacia and gliotic process noted in the left parietal lobe suggestive for chronic infarct. Small chronic right pontine infarct noted. There is no abnormal postcontrast enhancement intracranially. No evidence of intracranial hemorrhage, mass effect, edema, midline shift, hydrocephalus or extra-axial fluid collection. Therapeutic measures taken included physically therapy and occupational therapy. Clinical outcome of the events was not resolved. The events were assessed as serious (disability).   Follow-up attempts are completed. No further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Based on the temporal association, there was a reasonable possibility that the vaccination with BNT162B2 played a contributory role in triggering the onset of Walking difficulty and incontinent. The patient had a relevant medical history of kidney stones, drug allergy lyrica was manifested by headaches and mad, irritable bowel syndrome from crohn's disease, irritable bowel syndrome from crohn's disease, gastroesophageal reflux disease, guillain-barre syndrome, high blood pressure, non-alcoholic liver cirrhosis and primary sclerosing cholangitis. On unknown dates, the patient experienced two big blood clot in the lower left abdomen, cyst on left kidney/probably benign and recurring right and left kidney stones. In 2017, the patient experienced right kidney stones, low iron level, low platelets and low red blood cells. In Feb2020, the patient experienced intestinal blockage and intestinal blockage infection. In Mar2020, the intestinal blockage and intestinal blockage infection resolved. In Dec2020, the patient experienced crohn's disease flare up. In February 2021, the patient experienced portal vein thrombosis. On 19Mar2021, the patient experienced bad headache. On 21Mar2021, the bad headache resolved. In October 2021, the patient experienced portal vein thrombosis/bleeding. In 2021, the portal vein thrombosis resolved. On an unknown date, crohn's disease flare up resolved. Pfizer BioNTech COVID-19 VACCINE (TOZINAMERAN) was also considered suspect.  The patient had crohn's disease flare up in Dec 2020 and was hospitalized for a week. In Feb2021, he stayed for a week in the hospital due to the blood clot that was found. The patient took WARFARIN 5 milligram every tuesday, thursday and saturday and 7.5 milligram every monday, wednesday and friday. He had a blood clot in his abdomen and was placed on COUMADIN. Apart from the medicines given, there were some medicines not stated as he did not have the list with him, and he was advised to stop some of them. On 04Feb2021, he had surgery as an outpatient procedure where laser was used to blast the kidney stones on his right kidney. He had a stent placed to removed remaining parts of the kidney stone. He was recovered from surgery. The headache usually started the next day and lasted for almost two days after the vaccine was administered. The causality as per reporter for surgery was reported as no reasonable possibility. He had cyst on his left kidney that his physician stated it was probably benign. He confirmed that there were no test or procedure done for the cyst on his left kidney. He had intestinal blockage and was hospitalized for five days. Because of postal vein thrombosis, he was hospitalized for four days. As of 03 Nov 2021, his kidneys were being monitored every six months because of the kidney stones. There were 25 different medications that he was taking as of 03Nov2021. It was unknown if patient was enrolled in a COVID-19 Vaccine Trial. In Aug2020, he received 1st dose COVID-19 Vaccine manufactured by Pfizer/BioNtech. In Oct2020, he received 2nd dose COVID-19 Vaccine manufactured by Pfizer/BioNtech. In Jun2021, he received 3rd dose COVID-19 Vaccine manufactured by Pfizer/BioNtech.  The patient was treated with OXYCODONE, COUMADIN, WARFARIN, LOVENOX and LIDOCAINE.   The reporter's causality for the event(s) of portal vein thrombosis/bleeding, intestinal blockage, portal vein thrombosis, right kidney stones, low iron level, low platelets, low red blood cells, cyst on left kidney/probably benign and recurring right and left kidney stones with HUMIRA 40MG/0.4ML (ADALIMUMAB) was no reasonable possibility. The reporter's causality for the event(s) of intestinal blockage infection and bad headache was not provided. AbbVie's opinion is that there is no reasonable possibility that the events of portal vein thrombosis/bleeding, intestinal blockage, portal vein thrombosis, two big blood clot in the lower left abdomen, intestinal blockage infection, right kidney stones, crohn's disease flare up, low iron level, low platelets, low red blood cells, bad headache and recurring right and left kidney stones are related to HUMIRA 40MG/0.4ML (ADALIMUMAB). The reporter's causality for the event headache with Pfizer BioNtech COVID-19 VACCINE was unrelated; causality for the rest of events portal vein thrombosis, thrombosis, Crohn's disease aggravated, recurring right and left kidney stones, headache, renal cyst was not provided.  The reporter's assessment of the causal relationship of the events portal vein thrombosis, thrombosis, Crohn's disease aggravated, recurring right and left kidney stones, headache, renal cyst with the suspect product was not provided at the time of this report. Since no determination has been received, the case is managed based on the company causality assessment.  No follow-up attempts are possible. Company comment : This is a case of Covid-19 immunization (Revaccination with a different Covid-19 vaccine) concerning a 90-year-old, female patient, with no relevant medical history, who experienced the non-serious, unexpected events of memory impairment, presyncope, feeling hot, feeling abnormal and vaccination site warmth. The events occurred  1 day after booster dose of mRNA 1273 vaccine. The patient initially had J and J vaccine as primary dose, and had Moderna booster 8 months after. The patient felt foggy mentally, could not remember the names of her medications, could not understand simple words, her head was so heavy and she felt like she was going to black out. She was ok after an hour or two. The rechallenge is not applicable as there is no additional dose expected. The patient's age may be a confounding factor to the events memory impairment and feeling abnormal. The benefit-risk relationship of mRNA 1273 vaccine is not affected by this report.; Sender's Comments: This is a case of Covid-19 immunization (Revaccination with a different Covid-19 vaccine) concerning a 90-year-old, female patient, with no relevant medical history, who experienced the non-serious, unexpected events of memory impairment, presyncope, feeling hot, feeling abnormal and vaccination site warmth. SYMPTOM_TEXT: First night I had headache and chills, some muscle soreness during the night.   10 days later I got the Influenza vaccine.   Day after influenza vaccine I started to get severe pain in lower back (near coccyx), both glutes and legs.  I could not sleep as lying down or putting my legs up made it worse.  The next moring I took dexketoprofen  and at night cyclobenzaprine with lysine cloxinate, but the pain barely subsided.  I had to go to the emergency room the pain was so severe (9 or 10) I had to sleep sitting down that night.  At the ER they took an xray, said they could find nothgin wrong there- They gave me an injection of tramadol with ketorolac, and told me to see a neurologist the next day.  Next morning I went to a neurologist and he diagnosed sacroileitis (I had gone bike riding 5 days before).  I asked if it might be because of the covid and influenza vaccines recently, but he attributed the pain more to the bike ride.  The bike seat was hard and I was sore in genital area from that, but I felt no muscle soreness nor discomfort day after the ride. (I had not ridden a bike for over 30 years though)  .   The neurologist gave me an injection of diprospan (betamethasone) and prescribed Celebrex and the Lysine and ciclobenzaprine.   The pain has subsided a bit, but still I feel tingling in feet and at night the back pain and glute pain keeps me up.
OTHER_MEDS: euthirox, astorvastin, calcium Citrate +D  , daily multivitamin, prolia injection a week prior to vaccination
